<HEAD>Michigan Wins College Basketball's National Championship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Rumeal </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> made two free throws with three seconds left in overtime to give <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> its first national championship in collegiate basketball with an 80-79 victory over Seton Hall Monday night. The championship game in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Collegiate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Athletic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> tournament was the fifth to go into overtime and the first since <LOCATION> Loyola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, beat <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> 60-58 in 1963. <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> carried the <ORGANIZATION> Wolverines </ORGANIZATION> to the title with 31 points in the final, giving him an <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> tournament record 184, breaking the 24-year-old mark of 177 set by <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s coach, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>, took over the team just two days before the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> tournament began and coached them through six victories to the title.
