<HEAD>Yellowstone Fires' Troubleshooters Deployed At Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt ^By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEWARD, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The disaster expert whose crew saved two <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> towns from last summer's <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> firestorms now is plotting to defend another national park against the largest oil spill in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. `` Our mission is to find out where the marine wildlife and sea birds are today, then set priorities so the oil that kills them can try to be contained,'' said <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Liebersbach </PERSON>, a veteran <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> troubleshooter whose title is incident commander. <PERSON> Liebersbach </PERSON>'s team has found similarities here to <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>. `` In <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> we put firefighters on the ground. Here we're providing logistics for Ph.D. biologists who we're handling as a very intelligent resource, very delicately If they need a boat we get one, if they need a ham sandwich we make one. What they need we try to provide,'' <PERSON> Liebersbach </PERSON> said. The tanker <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> hit a reef near <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> on Good Friday night and bled 10.1 million gallons of crude oil into Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. Huge fingers of the slick are now extending westward through <LOCATION> Montague </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> toward the 660,501-acre Kenai Fjord National Park. The oil was less than 10 miles offshore from <LOCATION> Seward </LOCATION> on Sunday night, but calm seas and gentle breezes made its future course unpredictable. `` It's possible it could miss everything here,'' said <PERSON> Liebersbach </PERSON>, `` but to ignore it would be totally negligent. Knowing what we do, we have to prepare to mitigate it.'' Created by the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> National Interest Lands Conservation Act of 1980, the new national park is a necklace of bird rookeries, tidal pools, and whale playgrounds draped along 610 miles of the <LOCATION> Kenai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>'s eastern coastline. Located 100 air miles southeast of <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>, most of the park can be reached only by floatplane or boat. It attracted fewer than 60,000 hardy tourists last year, and is more hospitable to its critters than its visitors. Among the animals who cavort in the midnight sun amid the rugged grandeur of the park's coves and inlets are many endangered Humpback and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> gray whales, a few endangered Fin whales, and otters, sea lions, and seals. <PERSON> Liebersbach </PERSON> is in charge of a 40-member-and-growing team of pilots, support personnel, and environmental experts drawn from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> agencies, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, and <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Although <PERSON> Liebersbach </PERSON>'s home is Fairbanks, he was at a meeting of the government's 18 Class 1 disaster incident commanders in <PERSON> Reno </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, when his permanent eight-man core unit was activated at the request of the park service. `` The last time we were together was <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>, on the Storm Creek fire,'' said <PERSON> Liebersbach </PERSON>. `` We did n't expect to see each other again until summer.'' Last August and September, he was boss to several thousand civilian and military firefighters who faced down 200-foot walls of flame threatening to incinerate Silver Gate and <LOCATION> Cooke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mont </PERSON>. The two towns were saved but <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>'s fires charred nearly one million acres. <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, the team's planning chief, said the spill `` woke us all up and got us ready for the year. It looks like it could be a long one.'' The team set up shop in a small house near park headquarters in <LOCATION> Seward </LOCATION>. Up went the topographical maps. In came the photocopy machine, typewriters, and coffeemaker. Seven phone lines now ring constantly from dawn until midnight. `` An oil slick is like a fire line, it just keeps moving,'' said <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>.
