<HEAD>Ecology Group Warns Sarney He Responsible for Amazon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of leading Latin American writers, artists and scholars has told President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> he will bear `` historical responsibility'' for continued destruction of the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> rain forest. `` We believe that the historical responsibility for destroying the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> jungle is very great, and future generations of Latin Americans will not forgive it if everything possible is not done to avoid it,'' the Group of 100 warned un a letter, which was released Monday. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> has rejected international criticism of the deforestation of the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> basin as foreign interference in <LOCATION> Brazilian </LOCATION> affairs. The Group of 100 declared that `` to invoke national sovereignty to justify crimes against nature _ like those being committed against one of the richest and most complex ecosystems on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> _ appears puerile and dishonest to us.'' The group condemned `` criminal burning that razes millions of acres of tropical forests, the clearing of the jungle for colonization and transnational agriculture'' and `` the extermination of ethnic groups whose members are hunted down by the ` modernizers' of agriculture to take over their lands.'' The letter, signed by 28 leading Latin American writers and artists, was delivered to the Brazilian Embassy by group president and poet <PERSON> Homer </PERSON> <PERSON> Aridjis </PERSON>. Among its signatories are <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuentes </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquez </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Onetti </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, widow of the slain Chilean President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> <PERSON> Llosa </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ernesto </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>.
