<HEAD>Cuban Security Museum Displays Relics Of War With CIA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Museum of State Security displays the scorched tail of a small plane, plastic explosives, a tattered 2506 Brigade armband, assault rifles, a radio transmitter and a battered water can with a label in English. The artifacts are part of what <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> presents as its 30-year struggle with the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and dissident Cubans accused of trying to kill or overthrow President <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>. The museum, which opened this weekend, occupies a refurbished mansion in a once-wealthy neighborhood whose villas now house embassies or government offices. In a small plaza visible from the street, a power boat with a black hull, sea blue decks and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> markings looks at first glance like a private plaything in a country where such luxuries are rare. Closer examination reveals that the boat, driven by powerful Mercury engines, has heavy machine guns mounted fore and aft. <PERSON> Octavio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON>, the clean-cut, graying guide at the museum, said the vessel made coastal raids until it was captured by agents of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s special police force. Maps inside the museum are dotted with sites of `` imperialist aggression,'' a battle plan for the U.S.-sponsored Bay of Pigs debacle in 1961. There are a rogue's gallery of people accused of trying to kill <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> and relics of what is portrayed as a secret war on the regime he established 30 years ago. At the center of an upstairs room, in its own sealed plexiglas case, is a three-volume set of the yellow-bound proceedings of a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> investigation of 1975. The committee investigation disclosed bungled <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> attempts on <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s life _ once with an exploding cigar, for instance, and another time with poison powder that supposedly was scattered on the leader's clothing but did no harm. Asked why the evidence was not displayed, <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> first said, `` There have been so many attempts they could n't all be put in the museum.'' Later, he said he was n't sure the evidence still existed. He led the visitors into the Hall of Martyrs, lined with portraits of 88 agents of State Security described as having died fighting the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> exiles, counterrevolutionaries or other enemies. A brass plaque beneath each portrait gave the details. <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> said the museum's purpose `` is to bring to the people a cultural identity and to transmit a story for all visitors fundamentally about a fight and the atrocities carried out against us, and the aggressions of the last century.'' Asked why a meseum opened now to depict events of the 1960s, <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> said: `` The opportunity is now'' and, in the past, `` the revolution had other priorities.'' In first room of the museum are a giant photo of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> landing at <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> in 1898, during the Spanish-American War, and a huge copy of a letter written in 1895 by <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Marti </PERSON>, patron saint of Cuban independence. <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would `` continue to use <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> as a base to extend its power into the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>.'' The only other exhibit in that room is an enlargement of a letter <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> wrote in 1958, from a camp in the hills, telling his longtime friend and secretary <PERSON> Celia </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>: `` They're firing rockets at us in the mountains. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> was killed, and the Americans will pay dearly for this.'' He also wrote, just a year before gaining power: `` It's becoming clear to me that this war will go on much longer. It will have to go on against the Americans.''
