sheen of oil has worked its way inside a plastic boom stretched across the bay, they said. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> officials have conceded that beach cleanup efforts so far have been futile. But the company said it began a new assault with more effective gear, more workers and a floating command post. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. President <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Iarossi </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> planned to flush beaches by pumping seawater over them, then collect oil from the water with skimmers `` We intend not to leave until the job is done,'' <PERSON> Iarossi </PERSON> said. `` We intend to leave <LOCATION> Prince </LOCATION> <LOCATION> William </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> close to what it was before the tragedy.'' State officials have blasted <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s effort to scrub beaches as dismal and ineffective. Less than 4 percent of the thick crude has been recovered. The spill has fouled more than 800 miles of shoreline in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>, and the amount grows each day. <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON>, 42, was fired by <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> last week. The skipper admitted drinking before boarding the Exxon Valdez, according to court documents. Blood and urine samples taken nine hours after the accident indicated he was drunk. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Weeks </PERSON>, director of criminal prosecution for the state of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, said authorities in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> have had communication with a lawyer in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> representing <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON>. The tanker accident forced reductions in the flow of oil through the Alaskan pipeline, which carries nearly one-quarter of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' domestic supply of crude oil. <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said the flow was increased Sunday evening with word from the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> that tanker traffic would soon be allowed to return to normal. However, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> decided Monday to reinstate daytime-only restrictions on oil tanker traffic in <LOCATION> Prince </LOCATION> <LOCATION> William </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> after state officials raised concerns, spokesman <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Meidt </PERSON> said. Night traffic was allowed Sunday for the first time since the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION>, one of the two largest tankers in <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fleet, ran aground. But after a Monday meeting, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> decided to again limit traffic until all agencies are satisfied that <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION>, the operator of the <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> terminal, has the equipment to handle another spill, <PERSON> Meidt </PERSON> said. `` If something were to happen, let's make sure we have enough gear there to respond,'' he said. The pipeline usually carries 2 million barrels of crude a day. That had been reduced to 800,000 barrels a day, causing shortages at <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> refineries and sending oil prices higher. By Monday morning, the pipeline flow had been increased to 1.3 million barrels a day, spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratterman </PERSON> said. Pipeline company officials said they did n't expect the latest restrictions in tanker traffic to force another cutback in flow.
