<HEAD>Barge Capsizes on Ohio River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARKERSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A barge carrying 160,000 gallons of lye capsized on the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> on Monday, and authorities were trying to salvage the craft without a major spill, state and federal officials said. A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said small amounts of a 50 percent lye solution, also known as sodium hydroxide or caustic soda, could be seeping through vents in the barge. `` Common sense tells us, you assume there's some seepage,'' said Lt. Commander <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` But none has been detected. Because of its high alkalinity, lye is considered a hazardous chemical that could endanger aquatic life and drinking water, officials said. The barge, owned by <ORGANIZATION> PPG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, was one of 15 being transported by a tugboat around a sharp bend in the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bottom </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Murraysville </PERSON>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION> It broke away from the other vessels and drifted close to the rocky shore before running aground between <LOCATION> Parkersburg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ravenswood </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON> said. The outer shell of the 195-foot barge was punctured by a rock shortly before 9 a.m. Monday, <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON> said. The space between the two hulls flooded and the barge capsized. <ORGANIZATION> Kemron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Marietta </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, company hired by <ORGANIZATION> PPG </ORGANIZATION> Monday to monitor the incident, did not detect an alkalinity increase in the water surrounding the barge. `` It would almost take a catastrophic release to pose a major threat,'' <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON> said. In high concentrations such as the barge is carrying, lye will burn skin and eyes, <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON> said. Swallowing it can be dangerous, he said. `` Drinking water could be infected, so water intake users downstream have been notified,'' he said. The cleanup and removal of the barge is expected to take several weeks. PPG's salvage expert from <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, was to arrive early Tuesday, <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON> said.
