<HEAD>Land Values in Midwest Were Stable Despite Ravages of Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> economist says federal emergency aid `` probably helped stabilize land values in the Midwest'' last year after drought ravaged crops across the region. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said that surveys by the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, indicate that land prices did not decline in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> in June through November last year. Other surveys indicate that farmland prices rose in the Corn Belt in 1988, he said. Real estate is the main source of loan collateral for farmers. `` While drought assistance has helped stabilize the agricultural economy, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> estimates that 10,000 to 15,000 commercial farms faced loan repayment problems due to crop losses,'' <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> said. `` These stressed farmers represent 1.5 percent to 2.5 percent of all commercial farms.'' The Disaster Assistance Act of 1988 was signed into law last Aug. 11 as the scorching summer drought was still at its peak. The law provided up to $ 3.9 billion in federal aid and other measures to help farmers recover. <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>, writing in the April issue of Agricultural Outlook magazine, said that federal disaster assistance may turn out to be less than foreseen last fall `` because crop losses were smaller than expected.'' `` Also, qualification for drought assistance was based on the whole-farm average yield for each crop, rather than on a field-by-field basis,'' he said. `` The averaging-up of yields, where good fields offset poorer fields, excluded some farmers from qualifying in areas with scattered rainfall.'' Even so, <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> added, the combination of drought assistance and federal subsidized crop insurance `` has permitted thousands of farmers in hard-hit states to survive last year's bad weather with less financial suffering than had been anticipated.'' <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> said a full assessment of federal drought aid and insurance benefits can not be completed until all payments and indemnities have been disbursed. But preliminary figures show those had `` substantial stabilizing effects'' in the hardest-hit drought areas. But on Capitol Hill there have been grumblings that <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> has mishandled 1988 relief and has ignored drought conditions now prevailing in parts of the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, notably in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Department officials testified that more than 558,000 producers had received disaster payments and emergency feed assistance amounting to more than $ 2.7 billion nationally. In his report, <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> said that as of early February, more than $ 2 billion in drought payments and almost $ 1 billion in federal crop insurance benefits had been paid to farmers in the top eight states. Farmers in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Dakotas </LOCATION> _ where more than 80 percent of the commercial farms were in drought-stricken counties _ have received nearly a third of the drought payments made so far. Benefits paid to the eight states as of early February, in millions of dollars, included drought aid in the first column, federal crop insurance in the second, and the total in the third:
</TEXT>
