 Ill. 207 97 304 <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> 168 128 296 Minn. 242 60 302 Mont. 149 95 244 N.D. 332 187 519 S.D. 148 49 197 <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> 90 28 118 Wis. 120 7 127
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American ketchup makers and other tomato processors will have a Japanese competitor bidding for farmers' crops, says an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report The Kogome Co.. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest tomato processing company, announced it will open a $ 20 million plant next year in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Banos </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, to manufacture tomato products and fruit juice beverages `` Most, if not all, of the manufactured products likely will be exported to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to take advantage of future market openings for tomato and fruit drink products achieved under a recent U.S.-Japan agreement,'' the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. The agreement gives <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exporters of 11 product categories, including processed tomato products and fruit juices, greater sale opportunities in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bryand </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wadsworth </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural counselor in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, said the plant will produce institutional-size containers tomato ketchup from tomato paste bought from local manufacturers. In addition, he said, the plant will produce retail-size `` fruit-juice added'' drinks such as orange and apple in both carbonated and non-carbonated form.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dry bean situation has `` completely reversed'' itself from a year ago because of higher prices prompted by the 1988 drought. By January, the average farm price of dry edible beans was $ 29.60 per hundredweight, up from $ 13.40 a year earlier. Price increases were the greatest for beans hit hardest by the drought. For example, grower prices for navy beans in the week of Jan. 24 averaged $ 32 per hundredweight, compared with around $ 10 in January 1988, the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. Total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> output of dry beans dropped 26 percent to 19.2 million hundredweight last year, the agency reported. `` The sharpest decreases in production were for red kidney, pintos and navies, the beans grown in states with less irrigation,'' the report said. Another price factor is an improved outlook for bean exports because of poor harvests in several major importing countries, including <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` Domestic demand for beans could also improve this year because of recent media attention and industry promotional efforts,'' the report said. Beans are a nutritious food item and are noted for their fiber content.
</TEXT>
