<FIRST>r a PM-ComputerVirus     04-04 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Computer Virus,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cornell Says Ethics, Not Security, The Key to Preventing Computer
Worms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ethics, not increased security, are the best defense against computer `` worms'' like the one unleashed last fall by a <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> graduate student, a school official said. A special university commission reported Monday that <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> acted alone and with `` reckless disregard'' on Nov. 2 when he launched a debilitating program into the Internet network, causing thousands of computers around the country to clog and overload. The commission concluded that <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> did not intend for the worm to destroy data or files, but that he did want it to spread widely. It said the program was not technically a `` virus'' _ a program that inserts itself into a host program to propagate _ but was a `` worm,'' an independent program that replicates itself once placed in a computer system. Release of the worm was not a `` heroic event that pointed up the weaknesses of operating systems,'' contrary to <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>' claim, the commission wrote. The panel also denied that <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> was a genius for creating the worm. It said although the worm was technically sophisticated, it could have been created by many students. In fact, <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>' `` juvenile act'' did little to provide insights into the already well-known security flaws of the Internet system, a national research network used by universities, industry and government, said <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president of technologies. <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> Provost <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barker </PERSON> said the incident's greatest impact was the breach of trust it had caused among researchers who use the network However, both cautioned that employing drastic security steps was not a solution to prevent similar incidents. `` Violations of such a trust can not be condoned,'' said <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON>. `` A community of scholars should n't have to build sky-high walls in order to protect a reasonable expectation of privacy _ particularly when such walls would impede the free flow of information and ideas.'' <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> added that it's unlikely any security steps could guarantee an impenetrable system `` in a community of individuals possessed of all the knowledge and skills required to scale the highest barriers.'' Instead, the <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> officials stressed the need for improved awareness of computer ethics, said <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON>. `` I do n't think one can ever feel confident by putting bigger and tighter locks on the door,'' said <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON>. `` That's why it's important to stress ethical considerations. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, who is on a leave of absence from school, declined to be interviewed by the commission, which was left to speculate as to the reasons he created the `` worm.'' The panel made no recommendation about disciplinary action against the first-year graduate student in <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION>'s doctoral computer program. <PERSON> Barker </PERSON> said <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>' case would be reviewed by a panel of graduate students and faculty that could permanently bar him from the university. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, 23, of <ORGANIZATION> Arnold </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, remains under investigation by a federal grand jury in <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
