<FIRST>r a PM-Opera     04-04 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Opera,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Billy Budd Revived at Met</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The expanding shipboard set that dominates <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Britten </PERSON>'s `` <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Budd </PERSON>'' at the Metropolitan Opera is so spectacular that the work would almost be worth reviving just for the chance to see it in action. Luckily, there was also quite a bit of a musical nature to hold the interest Monday night when the company presented the <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> production for the first time in several seasons. <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Melville </PERSON>'s classic tale revolves around three sharply drawn characters who inspired some of <PERSON> Britten </PERSON>'s most memorable music: <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Budd </PERSON>, the good and handsome sailor; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Claggart </PERSON>, the evil master-at-arms who is bent on his destruction; and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Vere </PERSON>, the philosophical captain who reluctantly sends <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> to his death to preserve law and order. Two of the three roles were in excellent hands. Baritone <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> made a first-rate <PERSON> Billy </PERSON>, conveying first his youth and enthusiasm and later his pathos when, chained and awaiting execution, he sings a haunting ballad. As Vere, tenor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> made a moving figure, especially in the prologue and epilogue where he appears as an old man musing about the distant past. Another composer might have made <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> a tenor, the vocal part traditionally associated with a young hero. But in <LOCATION> Melville </LOCATION>'s ambiguous narrative, Captain Vere may be the real hero, and <PERSON> Britten </PERSON>'s decision to make him the tenor seems to acknowledge this The malevolent <PERSON> Claggart </PERSON> is portrayed more conventionally as a deep bass. <PERSON> Jan-Hendrik </PERSON> <PERSON> Rootering </PERSON> looked sinister enough, but his good-sized voice lacked the bite and menace that <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> brought to the part when the production was new. The men's chorus, which has a major role in the all-male cast, performed lustily, and the orchestra played well under conductor <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Fulton </PERSON>. But it was above all the set, designed by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dudley </PERSON>, that commanded admiration. With the aid of the Met's elaborate system of stage elevators, the ship expands and shrinks like an accordion as the action shifts from the main-deck, to the captain's cabin, to the quarter-deck, to the lower gun-deck. The effect is fittingly to make the ship itself the dominant image in the opera, a microcosm where the battle between good and evil is played out to its tragic conclusion.
</TEXT>
