<HEAD>Death Penalty Opponents Pressing D.C. Mayor To Block Extradition
Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opponents of capital punishment are pressing <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> to block the extradition of a juvenile sought by <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> until he's assured the youth wo n't face the death penalty But <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> so far has refused to interject himself publicly into the extradition case involving a 17-year-old black youth charged in the May 1988 firebombing of a <LOCATION> Gadsden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, apartment. A 14-month-old black child died in the fire. <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Blake </PERSON>, the mayor's deputy press secretary, said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> would not respond to pleas, made at a Monday news conference by a group of death penalty opponents and church leaders, that he refuse to honor <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'s extradition request unless state authorities guarantee the youth, identified by the initials <LOCATION> O.M. </LOCATION>, will not be charged with a capital crime. While <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> has remained silent, lawyers for the district government have supported <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'s bid to extradite the youth, who has been held in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> since his arrest in December on a fugitive warrant from <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. Superior Court Judge <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eilperin </PERSON> last week granted <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'s extradition request, but he stayed his order until today to allow the youth's attorneys to appeal. An appeal was filed Friday with the <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, which extended the stay until April 10. <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bronstein </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> can supersede the court ruling and block the extradition until <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> promises not to seek the death penalty. <PERSON> Bronstein </PERSON> charged that <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, by allowing his government to support the extradition, has `` forgotten the values that motivated him 25 years ago'' when he worked for racial justice in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> as a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nonviolent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coordinating </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> SNCC </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-. <PERSON> Bronstein </PERSON>, who was an attorney for <ORGANIZATION> SNCC </ORGANIZATION> members during the civil rights movement, said he was issuing `` a personal plea to the mayor ... do n't send this youngster back without the kinds of guarantees that will ensure us that he wo n't be killed in jail, that he will be treated in a decent fashion and that he wo n't face the death penalty.'' If <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> refuses to make such guarantees, then <PERSON> Bronstein </PERSON> said the district should release the youth, because there are no other outstanding charges against him. O.M.'s attorneys contend he can not get a fair trial from the white authorities of <LOCATION> Etowah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, because of their long-standing vendetta against his family. Both the boy's father and uncle died while in police custody. Another of the boy's uncles has been charged with murder and arson in connection with the 1988 firebombing. O.M. is charged under juvenile law as an accessory to the firebombing, and thus is not facing an immediate threat of the death penalty. But <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> authorities have refused to rule out the possiblity that he might be tried as an adult and subjected to the death penalty.
