<HEAD>President Mixes Diplomacy, America's Pastime</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Mideast Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> scoffs at the notion that his season-opening pitch to <ORGANIZATION> Orioles </ORGANIZATION>' catcher <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Tettleton </PERSON> was a high and wide. `` He caught it before it started breaking,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> protests. With guest Egyptian President <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> and a sellout Memorial Stadium crowd of 52,161 watching, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> tossed the first ball in Monday's American League opener between <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, captain of the 1948 <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> baseball team and an enthusistic lifetime fan, threw the ball lefthanded from the mound. Standing in his shirtsleeves with his jacket removed and a glove on his right hand, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> hurled the ball without benefit of a windup. <PERSON> Tettleton </PERSON>, who had moved several feet in front of home plate for the presidential pitch, gloved the curve ball with a long reach over his right shoulder. Over hot dogs, hamburgers and soft drinks, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> discussed that pitch _ his first game-opener as president _ with <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> and other guests and reporters in his glass-enclosed box over third base, voicing mock dismay over a reporter's suggestion that it was `` high and outside.'' Turning to baseball great <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, a longtime <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> friend, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said: `` Here's an objective judge. What did you think, sir?'' After a pause, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said: `` High, hard, fast ball.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> then asked `` another objective visitor,'' baseball commissioner <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> <PERSON> Giamatti </PERSON>. `` Superb,'' <PERSON> Giamatti </PERSON> said, adding he had n't seen the pitch but had heard about it from Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, who `` said it was wonderful.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Muburak </PERSON> left after the fifth inning, when <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> led 1-0, missing most of the action. The final score was <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> 5, <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION> 4 in 11 innings. <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON>, putting on an <ORGANIZATION> Orioles </ORGANIZATION> hat for photogrpahers, said he was enjoying both his hot dog lunch and his first live baseball game, calling <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` a very good teacher.'' `` He was the captain of the biggest team in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> said. `` That's what I told him,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> interjected. At <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>, first baseman <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was known more for his fielding than his hitting. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was asked if Monday's game brought back memories from his youth. `` This was fun, yeah,'' he said.
