<SECOND>PM-Lites, SUB, a0418,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS first item to DELETE INCORRECT reference to first official
nut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The hazelnut rolled past the giant chinquapin on the way to becoming the official state nut. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Monday passed the hazelnut on to the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for consideration. The only person to testify in favor of the giant chinquapin, a cousin of the chestnut, was <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Pope </PERSON>, a Salem seed company owner and nature lover who admitted that legislators might consider his favored nut `` squirrel food.'' He was no match against 10 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Slick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Camp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> from <ORGANIZATION> Clackamas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> and lobbyists for the $ 20 million hazelnut industry. `` Indians and pioneers ate hazelnuts,'' said troop member <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Stitt </PERSON>. Only one committee member voted against the hazelnut, also known as filberts. `` I'm not convinced this was an issue we need to address,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Springer </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
