<FIRST>r w PM-EducationSpending     04-04 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Education Spending,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>For release 9:30 a.m. EDT; time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Teachers' Union Says $10 Billion More Needed For School Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's largest teachers union today called for $ 10 billion in new federal spending to counter `` a shocking erosion'' in education programs for the disadvantaged and handicapped. `` These programs reach only a fraction of the young people they were meant to serve,'' <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said in issuing a report called `` Federal Education Funding: Present Realities and Future Needs.'' `` In state after state, the numbers in our new report clearly demonstrate a shocking erosion of federal support for these essential programs,'' <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> said in a statement. `` Nothing could be more impractical for our nation than continuing this systematic underfunding.'' <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> report contains the first estimates of what it would cost to serve all students currently eligible for help under four of the most important federal education programs. NEA has more than 1.9 million members across the country. Its report comes as <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> prepares to tackle the fiscal 1990 budget. The report looks specifically at Chapter 1, grants to bolster basic skills among disadvantaged youngsters; the Education for All Handicapped Act, which helps states educate disabled youngsters; bilingual education, grants to make sure students with native languages other than English succeed in school; and <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> grants for college students from low-income families. The most serious erosion appears to have occurred in Chapter 1. The <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> report said the number of students served dropped from 7 million in 1980-81 to 5.7 million in 1988-89. At the same time the number of children in poverty swelled, so while the program reached 65 percent of eligible students in 1980-81, it reached only 40 percent by 1986. For fiscal 1989, the group said, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> provided $ 4.6 billion for Chapter 1 _ enough to serve 47 percent of eligible students. To serve the estimated 8.5 million who will qualify next year, would cost about $ 6.9 billion _ a $ 2.3 billion increase over current levels. The authors of the 1974 handicapped act intended that the federal government would ultimately pay 40 percent of its cost to local school districts. But the federal share started at 12 percent and stayed there until 1980, and by fiscal 1989 had dropped to 7 percent, <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> said. To reach the 40 percent target would cost $ 8.4 billion, a $ 6.5 billion hike over current levels, the report said. And though funding has doubled since 1980, merely restoring the federal share to 12 percent would cost an extra $ 700 million. The bilingual education program currently serves one in 18 of students who need help in English language skills, <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> said. An increase of more than $ 1 billion would be needed to serve the 1.6 million students states report as eligible, the group said. While funds for <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> grants have increased slightly when adjusted for inflation, the increases have not come near matching the soaring costs of postsecondary education, <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> said. It also said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has `` fallen far short'' of meeting its own authorized funding level for the individual grants. Another $ 600 million would be needed to fully fund the maximum $ 2,900 Pell grants permitted in fiscal 1990, the teacher union said. Higher academic standards and a greater emphasis on analysis and problem-solving are `` doomed to failure unless schools and communities can maintain programs to help all students meet those standards,'' the report said. It says the solution, given state and local economic constraints, is to fully restore the federal share of support for public education. The <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> report was based on charts provided by <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, an independent statistical analysis firm.
</TEXT>
