<FIRST>r w PM-CongressionalMilestone     04-04 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congressional Milestone,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Congress Had First Quorum 200 Years Ago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this week celebrates a curious but important milestone: The 200th anniversary of the days on which the first House and first <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> achieved a quorum and were finally ready to begin the work of the new nation. The House marks the occasion today, April 4, three days after the actual April 1 anniversary. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> celebrates on Thursday, April 6, the actual date of its first working quorum. Commemorative postage stamps will be issued honoring the bicentennials of both houses. The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> established under the Constitution first convened in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> on March 4, 1789. But the absence of the required majority plus one prevented the two chambers from getting down to business. On that first day only 13 of the 59 <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members and only eight of the 22 senators were in attendance. Election complications, bad weather, muddy roads and just plain sloth get the blame as causes for the delay. The journal of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> noted with monotonous regularity that `` a quorum of the members not being present, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> adjourned.'' <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> under the discarded Articles of Confederation had been noted for absenteeism and near paralysis, and many feared history was about to repeat itself. `` We lose credit, spirit, everything,'' Rep. <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> <PERSON> Ames </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> wrote to a friend in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. `` The public will forget the government before it is born.'' The senators who had managed to reach <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> wrote to their absent colleagues: `` We apprehend that no arguments are necessary to evince to you the indispensable necessity of putting the government into immediate operation and, therefore ernestly request that you will be so obliging as to attend as soon as possible.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> had been elected the nation's first president, but could not enter office until the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> achieved a quorum and met to count the ballots of the <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. From Mount Vernon he grumbled that senators and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members were in a state of `` stupor or listlessness.'' But eventually the required numbers assembled. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, counting its first quorum on April 1 _ April Fool's Day some have noted _ elected <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Augustus </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhlenberg </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> as its first speaker And <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> <PERSON> Ames </PERSON>, much mollified now that work could begin, said he was pleased with his new colleagues. While there were few `` shining geniuses,'' he said, there were many who had `` experience, the virtues of the heart, and habits of business.'' On April 6 the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> counted its first quorum. The first order of business: Counting the votes of the electors and dispatching messengers to inform <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> that they had indeed been chosen president and vice president.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The postage stamp honoring the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> will display the gilt shield and eagle suspended over the presiding officer's chair in the Capitol's Old Senate Chamber, in use from 1810 to 1859. The stamp honoring the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> features the fanciful `` Car of History,'' a winged marble chariot which, since 1819, has borne the carved figure of Clio, the muse of history, over the floor of the Old House Chamber, now Statuary Hall. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Quincy </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, who served 17 years in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> after his single term as president, was inspired in 1840 to dedicate a poem to the muse who is shown recording in a book the events unfolding on the floor of the legislative body below. Often at odds with his colleagues and irritated by their conduct, <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> paid tribute to the muse for putting up with the `` wordy war'' conducted by the members. There was wit, there was wisdom, he acknowledged. But there was also `` the conflicting jar of ranting, raving parties, day and night ...'' <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> concluded: `` Oh! Muse historic _ in thy march sublime Still urging onward on the wheels of time. Canst thou not whisper to the chosen band But for one day to calm their senseless rage, And let thy volume bear one blessed page Of deeds devoted to their native land.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Knutson </PERSON> covers <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and its lore for The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
