<FIRST>r w PM-DebtTalks 690   04-04 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Debt Talks, 690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brady Looks for Quick Action on US Debt Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Will be topped around 9 a.m. EDT with final communique</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is challenging the world's democratic powers to move quickly and put in motion the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's plan for easing the Third World's politically explosive debt burden Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>'s proposals to ease the seven-year-old debt crisis were slated for a final review today from the executive committee of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. Some participants at the spring meeting of the two organizations have expressed concerns that unless action is taken on the <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan, political unrest could be unleashed in the fragile democracies of <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> where the huge debt burden has depressed living standards for most of this decade. At least 270 people were killed in riots in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> in February after the goverment imposed a new austerity program to satisfy creditors. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, in an address on Monday, told the organizations it was time `` to turn these concepts into specifics which provide a basis for lasting progress in dealing with the debt problem.'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>'s scheme marks a sharp turn from past <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy because it seeks for the first time to reduce the $ 1.3 trillion Third World debt by getting commercial banks to voluntarily forgive part of their loans. Although <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s allies were not in total agreement with every element of the plan, Canadian Finance Minister <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> predicted it would receive general approval. He told reporters that although much discussion had gone on about the technical problems of putting the plan in motion, `` there are no serious objections that have been put forward.'' The plan got a major boost on Monday when the Japanese stepped forward with a pledge to provide up to $ 4.5 billion in new loans to Third World debtors over the next several years. The funds, however, did not match the widely anticipated $ 5 billion to $ 10 billion expected from the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> government. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> also had been counting on other countries running large trade surpluses, such as <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, to recycle a part of their wealth into increased aid for developing nations. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> made clear there were some doubts about how completely the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plan would be adopted, saying its proposal to use <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> resources to guarantee interest payments raised `` all sorts of problems.'' <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> said the time had come for the commercial banks who had made the loans to do more to resolve the crisis by writing off debt without trying to shift the burden onto the backs of the international lending organizations. The <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> are supported by taxpayer funds from the 151-member countries, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is the largest contributor. `` What I do not find acceptable is the idea that our taxpayers should bail out the commercial banks,'' <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> told reporters at a briefing. The two large international lending agencies have a key role to play in the plan because they would be expected to put up about $ 12 billion each to guarantee to the banks that the remaining part of the debt or the annual interest payments would be repaid. The administration won general approval for its new approach from its six largest allies on Sunday, but the communique issued by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> promised only to `` examine'' the question of guaranteeing interest payments to the banks. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION>'s communique was more supportive of the less costly idea of guaranteeing the reduced level of debt. <PERSON> Mailson </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferreira </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON>, finance minister of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, the largest Third World debtor with $ 110 billion owed, praised the Brady initiative, calling it a `` major conceptual breakthrough'' with success depending on `` our capacity to move quickly and far enough.'' `` These new ideas raise new hopes,'' he said in his comments to the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> steering group. `` They should be translated into immediate action. It is crucial that such new hopes do not give place to new frustrations.''
</TEXT>
