<HEAD>South Korean Dissident Says He Doesn't Fear Arrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A South Korean dissident today called his unauthorized visit to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> a success and said he was ready to face arrest at home. `` I'm not nervous about my arrest but I hope I wo n't be arrested,'' Rev. <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ik-hwan </PERSON> told a news conference. The <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> government has said it will jail <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> for his trip to <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>. South Koreans are prohibited from visiting the north without government approval. Communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has warned that <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>'s arrest would hamper dialogue between the sides. In South Korean, authorities imprisoned two dissident leaders Monday in an apparent crackdown on dissent connected to the Moon visit. <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> said his wife told him by telephone Monday night that his three sons also had been arrested. Reports from <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> said the sons were under investigation. <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>, 71, has been arrested several times for anti-government activities since the 1970s. Asked why his sons had reportedly been detained, he smiled and said `` they have the wrong father.'' <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> arrived in the Chinese capital Monday after a nine-day visit to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. He said he planned to leave Wednesday for <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, but that he had not decided when he would return to <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. The English-language <ORGANIZATION> Korea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported today that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has asked <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to deny <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> a visa. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials said <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> had been granted a transit visa that would a