 Egyptian President <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> defended the scope and pace of his nation's economic reforms today and told members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> needs continued high levels of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic assistance. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> described the 90-minute private meeting between <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> and 15 senators as `` very beneficial and fruitful'' but said commitments on the aid issue were neither sought nor given. Both <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> said senators told the Egyptian president that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must keep the large <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> budget deficit in mind in dealing with all requests for economic and military assistance. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said senators appeared favorably impressed with <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON>'s description of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s economic reform program, including the reduction of subsidies on a number of consumer products and revisions in the country's tax structure. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> was asked if senators were satisfied at the pace of the <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> program. `` Obviously every national leader confronts the same general problem of the pace of economic reform,'' he replied. `` We confront a similar problem in dealing with our budget deficit.'' `` The president argued that the pace he is pursuing is the one most appropriate to their circumstances and the one most likely to bring success,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. On another subject, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> flatly denied reports that <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> intends to acqu