<HEAD>Gov't Heightens Crackdown on Labor, Student Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Riot police firing tear gas charged onto a university campus and into a housing complex Tuesday to put down violent anti-government protests in two cities. In <LOCATION> Ulsan </LOCATION>, about 150 miles south of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, thousands of workers hurling firebombs and rocks fought riot police to protest a crackdown on strikers at <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heavy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest shipyard, news reports said About 3,000 riot police stormed a complex of 150 high-rise apartments, a stronghold of militant stikers, after battling 5,000 workers and radical students on the streets, according to the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> news agency <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION>. Television footage showed protesters yelling and throwing rocks and firebombs from apartment balconies and roofs. Rocks rained down on police, who retaliated with tear gas. The Korean Broadcasting System said police retreated after several hours of battles that left about 60 police and workers injured. Police gave no figures on arrests or injuries in the six days of protest. Fighting has taken place daily in <LOCATION> Ulsan </LOCATION> since March 30 when 14,000 riot police stormed the shipyard to end a 109-day strike by 5,000 of the company's 19,500 workers who broke off from the company union. Militant workers demanded more pay and better working conditions. <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> officials say non-striking workers have been assaulted and attacked leaving the yard and the workforce has steadily declined. On Tuesday, about half the workers showed up. Stores, banks and schools near the shipyard must close part of every day as fighting erupts. <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> officials worry the labor unrest will spread to subsidiaries. <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION>, one of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s largest conglomerates, makes cars, steel, electronics and other products, and employs 100,000 people in <LOCATION> Ulsan </LOCATION>. Radical students attacked four <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> offices in three cities, burning two cars and breaking windows, <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION> said. In western <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, police in visored helmets stormed the campus of <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, firing tear gas to disperse an anti-government rally by 1,000 students. In the last two years, police have stayed on the perimeters of colleges and fought students mostly in and around school gates. The students burned an effigy of President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>, then drove police back by hurling firebombs and rocks. They shouted: `` Down with <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>, who blocks unification and stifles workers' rights!'' The fighting continued about an hour, and police said more than 400 students from other colleges were arrested for trying to enter <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> to take part in the protest after school gates had been sealed off by thousands of police. One student was injured in the head by police hurling rocks. The students were protesting the police action in <LOCATION> Ulsan </LOCATION> and supporting the trip to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> by a dissident, the Rev. Moon Ik-kwan. <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>'s unauthorized visit has provoked controversy in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, where government officials say he was serving interests of communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. It has sparked a government crackdown on dissidents, with security officials arresting <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>'s colleagues and questioning others. Security agencies and police raided dissident offices and homes Monday. Dissidents alleged the government was using <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>'s trip as an excuse to crack down on dissent. Radicals students are a vocal minority with little public support.
