<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAR2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Frigid weather chilled <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> on Tuesday, bringing <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> its first snowfall since the winter of 1987-88. The blustering cold followed days of balmy weather crowned by spring blossoms that started sprouting a week ago as temperatures soared to the 70s. Tuesday's early morning temperatures hovered around freezing in the northern half of the country with gusts of wind reaching 30 mph. The snow coated trees and lawns but did not disrupt morning traffic because it melted as soon as it hit the streets. The <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> weather bureau said the impression that a cold wave had struck stemmed from the contrast between the freezing temperatures and the warm weather last week. Forecasters said snow and cold temperatures are normal for early April in the northern part of the country. In the south, in <LOCATION> Provence </LOCATION> and along the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Riviera </LOCATION>, where there was concern about the lack of moisture, one-half to nearly 2 inches of rain fell in the past 24 hours. Rain also fell in the Pyrenees along the Spanish border. In the English Channel, winds gusted up to 50 mph and waves of 20 feet were reported off the <LOCATION> Channel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. Snow and sleet hit <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, chilling residents who also had been enjoying warm weather. Temperatures dropped to 36 degrees and the winds picked up. Over the weekend, Belgian beaches saw the first sunbathers in swimsuits and the public parks were full of families enjoying 68-degree temperatures. But on Tuesday, the weather office reported more than an inch of snow _ the first in more than a year _ in central <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>. Forecasters said temperatures were expected to warm up again later this week.
