<HEAD>NATO Turns 40 _ Still Cautious About Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BRU2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance, shaped out of the fears of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> expansionism, turned 40 on Tuesday with Western officials expressing caution and uncertainty about the dramatic changes gripping the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Manfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON>, secretary-general of the 16-nation <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will still remain a strong military power even if promised cuts are carried out in troops and military spending. `` The intentions of the current <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leadership ... are peaceful ones,'' <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> told a news conference at <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>. Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, he said, `` does n't want to wage a war.'' But he cautioned, `` There is still a risk because intentions may change. We have no control over them. Personalities, leaders may change.'' <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON>'s remarks capped a morning of ceremonies marking the signing of the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> treaty on April 4, 1949, forming a security alliance that links the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> with Western European nations. The Western nations joined the pact to unite against the threat of expansionism posed by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in the years following World War II. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s recent agenda of economic and social reforms and his promises of military cuts have diminished the public's perception of that threat and raised questions about <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s role. Anniversary speeches, celebrations and a few protests held elsewhere in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> reflected the new situation. British <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Younger </PERSON>, in a speech at <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> offices north of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, credited the alliance with helping bring about `` the long overdue changes'' under way in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Five members of the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disarmament </ORGANIZATION> demonstrated outside the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> complex, undeterred by a rare spring sprinkling of snow. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> officials served them hot tea. In <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norwegian </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Gro </PERSON> <PERSON> Harlem </PERSON> <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> called <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> `` the most successful alliance we know'' and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Thorvald </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoltenberg </PERSON> called it `` more important than ever.'' A small group of protesters in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, including <ORGANIZATION> Greens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> deputy <PERSON> Gianni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattioli </PERSON>, organized a conference called `` 40 Years Is Enough.'' They demonstrated outside the premier's office and particuarly objected to the scheduled relocation of a squadron of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> F-16 fighters from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. A naval exercise and marching bands marked the anniversary in <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION>, while a few hundred peace activists staged a demonstration. No incidents were reported. <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON>, former German defense minister, led off the outdoor celebrations at <ORGA