<HEAD>Namibian Police Are Combat-Hardened Veterans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Namibian policemen battling black nationalist guerrillas are combat-hardened fighters more accustomed to <PERSON> bush </PERSON> warfare than routine law enforcement. The black patrolmen and their mainly white South African officers wear military uniforms and move about in heavily armored personnel carriers equipped with machine guns. They have played a leading role in fighting guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> since a special police counterinsurgency unit was formed in 1979, 13 years after the black nationalist fighters began the war for independence from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Known as `` <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION>'' _ the <LOCATION> Afrikaans </LOCATION> word for crowbar _ the unit officially was disbanded in January as a goodwill gesture after <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> agreed to end its rule of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. However, most of <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION>'s estimated 3,000 men were integrated into the regular police and were ready for combat when heavy fighting erupted Saturday as a cease-fire was suppposed to take effect. Guerrilla leaders accuse police of initiating the fighting by hunting down guerrilla units which had no intention of staging attacks. Under the U.S.-sponsored <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> plan for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s independence, guerrilla and South African troops as well as those of the South-West African Territorial Force were to be confined to their bases from Saturday The territorial police force of 8,300 men was entitled to operate freely, with full responsibility for maintaining law and order during the transition to independence. More than 90 percent of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s policemen and soldiers of its territorial force are blacks. They are led by white officers, mainly South African. Most South African army troops in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> are white. <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION>'s history is clouded with controversy. Its effectiveness is widely acknowleged, but many Namibians attribute its success to ruthlessness. Several dozen of its members have been accused of atrocities against civilians, although only a few have been convicted. <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION> claims to have killed 2,812 guerrillas between 1979 and 1988 for the loss 132 black and 19 white members. Leaders of the guerrilla's legal political wing in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> describe <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION> members as `` programmed killers'' who will be required to undergo `` reorientation'' if the guerrillas win independence elections. Defenders of <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION> say the criticism is tacit acknowledgement of the unit's prowess. `` Counterinsurgency work is not very easy, and sometimes things get a little tense,'' Koevet commander Gen. <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Dreyer </PERSON> said last month. `` But without the support of the local people, we would not have had any success.'' In a standard <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION> operation, four armored personnel carriers with 10 blacks and a white commander each would head into the <PERSON> bush </PERSON> for a week at a time, questioning villagers and looking for traces of guerrillas. <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION> trackers sometimes would follow a trail for days, even crossing into <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, where most of the guerrillas are based. Most Namibian policemen are recruited in the north of the country among the Ovambo people who are famed for their tracking and other bush skills. The guerrillas almost always were on foot, and often were mismatched when overtaken by the personnel carriers or by helicopter gunships which <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION> would call in.
