<HEAD>Deficit Shouldn't Stand in Way of Handicapped Education: NEA President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal deficit should not be an obstacle to serving all handicapped and disadvantaged students eligible for help under federal programs, the president of the nation's largest teachers union said Tuesday. `` I do not believe that the children of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> created the deficit,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON>, president of the 1.9 million-member <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The organization is calling for an extra $ 10 billion in federal education spending to counter `` a shocking erosion'' in services under four major programs for disadvantaged students, low-income college students, handicapped students and students with limited proficiency in English. In a report called `` Federal Education Funding: Present Realities and Future Needs,'' the group says many federal programs reach only a fraction of those they are meant to serve. Serving all students currently eligible for the four programs would cost more than $ 10 billion, it says. `` I'm not an expert so I ca n't say where we would get the money,'' <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> said at a news conference. But she said the union has offered to sit down with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to look at the overall budget and re-arrange priorities. `` We are aware of the fact that we ca n't do this in one year,'' <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> said. `` It might take five years or 10 years. But what's important is that we recognize the problem ... and make the commitment to fully fund these programs in 1993 or 1998. The report looks specifically at Chapter 1, grants to bolster basic skills among disadvantaged younsters; the Education for All Handicapped Act, which helps states educate disabled youngsters; bilingual education, grants to make sure students with native languages other than English succeed in school; and <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> grants for college students from low-income families. The <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> reported the following statistics: _ Chapter 1 The number of students served declined from 7 million in 1980-81 to 5.7 million in 1988-89. The program reached 65 percent of eligible students in 1980-81 but only 40 percent by 1986. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> provided $ 4.6 billion for Chapter 1 in fiscal 1989, enough to serve 47 percent of eligible students. To serve the estimated 8.5 million who will qualify next year would cost about $ 6.9 billion, a $ 2.3 billion increase over current levels. _ Handicapped The federal share of costs to local school districts started at 12 percent 15 years ago and was intended to rise gradually to 40 percent. Instead it stayed at 12 percent until 1980 and has fallen to 7 percent today. To reach the 40 percent target would cost $ 8.4 billion, a $ 6.5 billion hike over current levels. _ Bilingual education Such programs serve one in 18 of students who need help in English skills. An increase of more than $ 1 billion would be needed to serve all 1.6 million students states say are eligible. _ Pell grants Such funds have increased slightly when adjusted for inflation, but the increases have not come near matching the soaring costs of postsecondary education. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has `` fallen far short'' of meeting its own authorized maximum fore individual grants. Some $ 600 million would be needed to fully fund the maximum $ 2,900 Pell grant permitted in fiscal 1990. The <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> report was based on charts provided by <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, an independent statistical analysis firm, and statistics from government agencies including the <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>.
