<HEAD>Interior Secretary Says Spill Could Harm Oil Development</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs new from morning hearing, picks up 2nd graf
pvs: Lujan's remarks xxx</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The massive Alaskan oil spill could put the brakes on petroleum exploration there and in other areas _ at least temporarily _ Environmental Protection Administrator <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> said today. `` We will take apart the environmental planning for every aspect of oil development in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and in other sensitive areas where the environment potentially could be threatened.,'' <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> appropriations subcommittee Asked by Rep. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Traxler </PERSON>, D-Mich., if the disaster in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> would prompt a re-evaluation of the environmental threat posed by oil development policy, <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> added: `` We are doing that, as you know, off the coast of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and the coast of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> - looking at three proposed lease sales there for oil and gas that appear to have significant environmental concerns associated with them We'll do it in <LOCATION> Prince </LOCATION> <LOCATION> William </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> and look very carefully at future contingency planning there. And we'll do it on the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sslope </LOCATION>. I think we owe that to the environment. We owe that to common sense.'' Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, asked <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> if he meant that the administration would not move forward on a controversial proposal for oil exploration in the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION> until a review had been completed. `` There is a very clear understanding that we will not move forward if we have any significant concerns that have not been resolved, yes sir,'' he responded. <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>'s comments came just a day after <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said the oil spill off <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> could become the petroleum industry's Three Mile Island if steps are n't taken to assure the public that oil developers are capable of protecting the environment. <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>'s remarks to an oil and gas industry conference Monday suggested the massive spill last month into Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> off <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> by the tanker <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> could have long lasting effects on the petroleum industry if some public damage control is not undertaken. `` It takes a long, long time to recover from these things,'' said <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>, comparing the Exxon Valdez spill to the accident a decade ago at the <LOCATION> Three </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> nuclear plant in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. The nuclear industry has yet to recover from that accident. `` If the image of an uncareful and uncaring industry prevails among the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> public, then we can kiss goodbye the domestic oil and gas development in -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> Arctic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, offshore and in the public lands,'' <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> told a conference of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ocean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The group represents about 235 companies involved in offshore oil exploration and drilling. <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>, nevertheless, emphasized that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration continues to support `` environmentally sound'' oil development in the arctic refuge and declared, `` Unless we pursue a coordinated policy to develop this country's domestic energy sources, including offshore oil and gas, every American will pay dearly for our failure.'' President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> generally has supported offshore drilling, but in one of his first steps as president ordered a review into the proposed sale of oil leases involving two areas off the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> coast and one off the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> because of environmental concerns. On the spill from the Exxon Valdez, the worst oil tanker spill in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history, <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> said inadequate recovery equipment likely prevented any chances of an effective cleanup within hours after accident. The vessel ran aground during the early hours of March 24 outside the port of <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. `` If it happened -LRB- again -RRB- someplace now you'd have the same disastrous situation,'' the <ORGANIZATION> interior </ORGANIZATION> secretary told reporters after his speech to the petroleum industry group. <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> said a key lesson learned from the accident is that cleanup equipment and preparedness for such a disaster must be improved. `` We need to be a little bit more prepared,'' said <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>. `` ... I understand about 80 percent of the oil was lost in the first hour or two. I do n't know that we could ever have contained it. Maybe it got away too quick.'' Later he told reporters, `` The kind of equipment that we have -LRB- available -RRB- ... is n't enough to take care of a spill like this.'' He said it was found that floating containment booms broke and oil skimmers were of little help. The characterization that the cleanup effort was doomed within hours of the accident has been disputed by some <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> fishermen, who have complained that opportunities were missed when little was done while relatively calm weather prevailed for two days after the accident. Oil company officials have acknowledged they did not begin to deploy cleanup booms around the hemorrhaging tanker until at least 10 hours after the accident. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> officials have blamed some of the delay on the government for not providing an early go-ahead to use chemicals to disperse the oil, while fishermen and state officials have accused the oil company of misleading them as to their cleanup capabilities.
