<HEAD>Air Force Finds Lubricant Problems in Many B-1B Bombers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has discovered a problem with lubricant levels in a wing gear box on its B-1B bomber fleet that is slowing the return of the bombers to the air, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s chief spokesman, said the <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> had cleared the B-1B bomber fleet to return to flight status on Sunday as individual planes underwent a final safety check, and more than 35 of the planes would be flying Tuesday. During the course of the final safety checks, however, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> mechanics began discovering a problem with gear boxes that are part of the assembly to move the wings back and forth, the spokesman continued. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> now expects roughly 90 of the B-1B's to be certified for flight operations by the weekend The problem involves a loss of the lubricant contained inside a sealed gear box that handles what is known as the angle gear drive shaft, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. That angle gear drive shaft is a key component of the wing-moving assembly. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, of 80 B-1B's receiving the final safety inspection so far, 70 showed insufficient lubricant levels inside that gear box. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> denied Tuesday the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> had uncovered any evidence showing that a loss of lubricant in that gear box was the cause of a March 27 incident that led to a week-long grounding of the B-1B fleet. In that incident, a B-1B undergoing a pre-flight check at <ORGANIZATION> Dyess </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, suffered a tear in a fuel tank when the left wing swung too far forward. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> disclosed Tuesday that accident investigators probing the mishap had discovered a fractured `` quill shaft'' in a main wing gear box and a fractured `` angle gear drive shaft.'' Other sources, who insisted on anonymity, said the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> `` does now suspect that a lubricant seal problem led to the March 27 mishap,'' probably by allowing too much torque pressure to build up on the shaft. `` At first blush, that's exactly what we believe caused the wing to go too far,'' said one source. `` There's a very definite connection.'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, referring to the two fractured shafts, said `` we do n't know what sequence those occurred in. `` We do n't know what the first cause was yet _ whether it was a procedural problem, a maintenance problem or a hardware problem. But simply in the course of investigating every possible problem that they could have had, they did discover this potential problem -LRB- with the lubricant -RRB-.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said the sealed gear boxes were manufactured by the <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and when mechanics were finding one with insufficient lubricant, it was being replaced and sent off to the contractor for repair. `` I think it's fortunate we had the incident at <LOCATION> Dyess </LOCATION> on the ground, because that led to the kind of detailed investigation that enabled us to catch something that we might not have caught,'' added one <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> source. The four-engine B-1B is the first addition to the manned bomber force in more than 25 years. To improve its performance, the plane features wings that can be swept forward or backward in flight. The wings are normally swept back for high-speed attack runs and forward for takeoffs and landings. Built by the <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the B-1B has a maximum speed of about 1,000 mph and a range of more than 7,000 miles. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> built 100 of the planes during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to modernize the old B-52 bomber force while it developed the new B-2 stealth bomber. Three B-1B's have been lost in accidents, leaving 97 in the fleet.
