he <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, for its part, is asking <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to rein in its troops, who were scheduled to begin demobilizing Sunday once the peace agreement went into effect and <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeepers were deployed. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> position is that <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> must withdraw the forces it has sent into <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> to north of the 16th parallel in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>,'' Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said. Under the peace agreement, <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas were supposed to stay in their Angolan bases, about 100 miles north of the Namibian border. She said that despite rebel claims, there was no doubt that the guerrillas had crossed the border on Saturday. Guerrilla officials and the Angolan government claim the fighters have been in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> for some time and fired in self defense after security forces attacked them. Villagers in northern towns, most of whom support the rebels, said they believe the guerrillas left <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> to return home and did not expect a fight because the independence process officially has begun. Asked whether the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> force, which has just 1,000 of its planned 4,650 soldiers deployed so far, should have foreseen the <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> incursion, Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> replied that `` hindsight is always great, but I do n't think anybody anticipated this.''
