<HEAD>Shamir's Plan Centers on Elections But Palestinians Reject Terms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Mideast, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The peace proposals Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> will submit to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> focus on elections in the occupied territories to choose Palestinians who would negotiate with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> on limited self-government. Many prominent Palestinians welcome the idea of balloting but argue that free elections can not be held as long as <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops occupy the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. In interviews and through his aides, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said he was willing to have Palestinians choose mayors to speak for major population centers or political figures to represent the whole region. The elected Palestinians would then meet with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> negotiators to work out a temporary solution for the 1 million residents of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and the 650,000 inhabitants of the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. The most Palestinians could expect from this process would be limited self-rule with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops still stationed in the occupied lands. But <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> has said troops could be pulled out of population centers once an autonomy scheme was agreed upon. Under <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s proposals, the final status of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> would be the subject of further negotiations after autonomy was implemented. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s advisers also hint he is ready to release some Palestinian prisoners and take other steps to reduce tension. However, they link any change to a truce in the <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> uprising _ intefadeh in Arabic _ in which 419 Palestinians and 18 Israelis have died since December 1987. `` The condition is that life in <LOCATION> Judea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Samaria </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> -RRB- must return to normal. The intefadeh must end,'' said <PERSON> Yossi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahimeir </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> spokesman. The Shamir ideas closely parallel the 1978 U.S.-mediated Camp David Accords signed by <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> but rejected by the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. The major difference is that <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> proposes electing negotiators before autonomy is implemented instead of members of an autonomous council after self-government is defined in talks. `` I believe that this will be the one big and important contribution that Mr. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> is bringing to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>,'' said an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> official who described the proposal as a `` major change'' in the government's position. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, however, rules out direct or indirect talks with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, which means elected representatives could not act as intermediaries. He gives Palestinians little hope of seeing an end to occupation because he has rejected <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> demands for statehood and refused to endorse the idea of returning any captured land to <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> sovereignty. In this, the right-wing prime minister takes a harder line than Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> and Finance Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, the leaders of the left-of-center <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> which shares power in the coalition government. Labor supports returning some of the captured land in exchange for peace agreements. Municipal elections have been held twice in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> since