<HEAD>Refusenik Given Permission to Leave for Medical Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Jewish refusenik whose emigration case had been pressed by British officials said Tuesday he was given permission to receive medical treatment in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The case of <PERSON> Georgy </PERSON> <PERSON> Samoilovich </PERSON> has been on a list <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> intends to raise with Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who is to arrive in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on Wednesday. `` Undoubtedly, the two events are connected,'' <PERSON> Samoilovich </PERSON>, 66, said in a telephone interview. `` This is happening only thanks to the work of the two governments, the British and the American, and the work of my friends throughout the world.'' In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> spokesman speaking on condition of anonymity said the action `` reflects a considerable achievement in Anglo-Soviet relations.'' The list Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> plans to discuss includes the wife of <PERSON> Oleg </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordievsky </PERSON>, a top Soviet spy who defected to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> in 1985, officials confirmed Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> refused to say how many people are on the list. The Soviet decision came a day after a protest by about 40 refuseniks in front of the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> who said they hoped the talks in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> would help resolve their cases. <PERSON> Samoilovich </PERSON>, who has life-threatening lymphoma, first applied to emigrate in 1979. He was sacked from a defense-related job and the Soviets have refused repeated applications on grounds he was involved with secret work. <PERSON> Samoilovich </PERSON> argues that everything he knew is now public material. Officials of the Soviet visa office summoned him Tuesday and told him the prohibition on his emigration due to access to state secrets had been removed, <PERSON> Samoilovich </PERSON> said. Refuseniks accuse Soviet officials of applying regulations that allow them to deny emigration because of access to secrets in many inappropriate cases. He said he was told he would be allowed to leave for medical treatment in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, and that his wife <PERSON> Vera </PERSON> and son, <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON>, would be allowed to emigrate after they submit new documents to Soviet officials. <PERSON> Samoilovich </PERSON> said he hoped to receive his international passport Wednesday or Thursday after using his internal Soviet passport to prepare legal documents testifying that the entire family wishes to leave. Once in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> he said he hoped not to return to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, but would wait in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> for his family. The family hopes to settle in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where it has close friends, <PERSON> Samoilovich </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Samoilovich </PERSON> has been offered free medical treatment both at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s state-run <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marsden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> and in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Hackensack </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. A Geneva-based agency that helps to resettle Soviet Jews said Tuesday the number who arrived in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> in March was 3,893, a 10-year high. But it said only 114, or 2.9 percent, wanted to go to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Most of the rest intended to go to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Reghina </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucault </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Intergovernmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Migration </ORGANIZATION>. Jewish emigration from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> reached a peak of 51,328 in 1979 but then dropped sharply and in the mid-1980s only about 1,000 a year were released. In the past two years, however, many long-time refuseniks have been permitted to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the number of emigres increased to more than 20,000 in 1988.
