 Rescuers on Tuesday pulled three more bodies from the wreckage of a train that derailed and slammed into a station in this southern city, bringing the death toll to eight. Authorities said 17 people were injured, one critically, in the accident Monday. Casualties occurred both on the train and in the station. Police identified the dead as the two train engineers, the chief of the station and two assistants, a railroad worker, a passenger on the train and a passenger in the station. The eight-car train derailed as it entered the station. Two cars slammed into the station wall, demolishing the bar, ticket booth, and freight and baggage section. Railroad authorities said the train apparently arrived at the station at a greater speed than the customary 18 mph. The Italian news agency <ORGANIZATION> AGI </ORGANIZATION> reported the train was traveling at more than 60 mph. National Transportation Minister <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> <PERSON> Santuz </PERSON> ordered an investigation into the crash.
