<SECOND>AM-Nader-TV,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lack of Public Affairs Programming Decried</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The rights of television viewers are being trampled by laissez-faire federal regulators who no longer require TV stations to broadcast public affairs programming, consumer advocate <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Nader </PERSON>, appearing at a news conference to discuss a study that said there has been a 51 percent decrease in issues-oriented public affairs TV programs since 1979, called for reinstatement of the Fairness Doctrine and requirements that broadcasters devote certain percentages of their broadcasting hours to non-entertainment programming. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 repealed the 40-year-old Fairness Doctrine, which had required broadcasters to cover controversial issues. In 1984 the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> revoked rules that obligated broadcasters to alot 5 percent of their programming between 6 a.m. and midnight to local shows, 5 percent to news and public affairs programs and 10 percent to general interest items such as as gardening, religion and advice-type shows. <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> under Chairman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> and his predecessor, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, was a `` rogue agency that has dangerously transformed power from the public to private commerce in sheer violation of the -LRB- 1934 Communications Act -RRB-.'' <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> said <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>'s view was `` audiences have no First Amendment rights.'' <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, and now <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>, maintained that marketplace pressures would force station owners to broadcast issues-oriented programs. That has not happened, <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> said, and the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> refuses `` to respect the access rights, the response rights of the audience.'' <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> said that the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> has abdicated its responsibility to monitor the broadcasting industry and that if it had it would have found an erosion of public interest programming in the wake of the 1984 repeal of the so-called 5-5-10 guidelines. The study by Essential Information, a public interest group that <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> founded in 1982, examined TV listings for programs at 217 stations in 50 markets on seven days in early 1988. The listings were compared with FCC-required program logs from 1975, 1978 and 1979. The study did not include cable TV. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON>, who wrote the study, said, `` The results show a 51 percent decrease between 1979 and 1988 in the average percentage of issue-oriented public affairs programming.'' He also said that `` the average percentage of time devoted to public affairs has decreased 39 percent, with 30 percent of <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> affiliates and 63 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> affiliates neglecting to air a locally produced public affairs program.'' <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON>'s study also showed there has been an 74 percent increase in news programs, and sharp increases in home shopping, real estate and program-length `` commercials'' such as how to lose weight or get rich. <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> said the report `` sounds terribly bogus. We have increased the number of stations over the last 10 years, both television and radio, by half and news and public affairs programming makes money. I find it incredible to think that the amount of this programming would go down. So I do n't know how he counted it, but I think it's subect to being recounted.'' Regarding the Fairness Doctrine, <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> said the `` commission found that it decreased the amount of public interest programming available, ... which was the opposite of what it was intended to do.''
