<HEAD>Chronology of Events in Haiti</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Haiti, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Chronology of events in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>: Oct. 22, 1957 _ <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> `` Papa Doc'' <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> becomes president in disputed election and in 1964 proclaims himself president for life. April 21, 1971 _ <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> dies and 19-year-old <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> `` Baby Doc'' <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> becomes president. Feb. 7, 1986 _ <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> flees to exile in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> after a month of anti-government unrest leaves more than 50 people dead. A three-man junta led by <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON>'s army chief of staff, Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON>, takes power. March 29, 1987 _ Voters overwhelmingly approve a new constitution putting elections for a president and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in the hands of a civilian election commission. Nov. 29 _ Election Day. Thugs kill at least 34 voters and confiscate ballots. The election is called off three hours after it begins. <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> and junta dissolve election commission. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> suspends $ 70 million in aid in protest. Jan. 17, 1988 _ <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON>, a 57-year-old university professor, is elected president in the newly scheduled elections. Few Haitians vote, and most opposition leaders refuse to participate. June 19 _ Troops storm the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palace </ORGANIZATION>, deposing <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> and replacing him with <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON>. <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> abolishes the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> a day later. Sept. 17 _ <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> is ousted in a coup led by noncommissioned officers and exiled in the neighboring <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>. Sept. 18 _ Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Prosper </PERSON> <PERSON> Avril </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and a former <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> adviser, declares himself president. March 13, 1989 _ <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> partially restores the suspended 1987 constitution. March 28 _ Four high-ranking army officers are reportedly accused of drug trafficking and discharged. The action comes one day after a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official ties resumption of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to progress in stopping the drug trade. April 2 _ Gunfire breaks out at the presidential palace. The government later says it has foiled a coup attempt by rebel officers. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> says loyal soldiers rescued <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> as he was being driven away to be deported. April 3 _ <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> goes on national television to announce that the coup has ended unsuccessfully and says power-hungry soldiers were behind it. April 4 _ Government placates rebel soldiers by releasing and deporting three army officers who led the coup attempt against <PERSON> Avril </PERSON>. Rebel soldiers accept new commander and insurgency seems over.
