<HEAD>Gold Treasures From West Africa Begin U.S. Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A glittering collection of gold jewelry and ornaments from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, where gold was shunned in ancient times as an evil spirit, begins a three-year, nine-city tour of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Wednesday at the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION>'s National Museum of African Art The handiwork of goldsmiths from <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mali </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION> comes from the private Barbier-Mueller Museum of <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, which houses one of the finest collections of African gold sculpture in the world. More than 150 handmade objects, comprising about half of the Barbier-Mueller collection, are going on display at the <LOCATION> Smithsonian </LOCATION>. They include elaborate necklaces, rings, hair jewels, pendants, masks, earrings, beads and ceremonial regalia such as gold-decorated fly whisks, sword handles and staffs. Guest curator <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrard </PERSON>, a British historian and authority on the gold trade in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, said gold dust and nuggets long were regarded with fear by natives who believed they would cause blindness and insanity. Africans began their goldsmith traditions in the 5th century, when European traders, alerted by slave merchants, sailed down the west coast of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> or crossed the <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> in caravans from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to trade salt and spices for gold. Very little of ancient West African gold jewelry exists today because it was lost in trade, looted from burial grounds and melted down to make coins or new ornaments. <PERSON> Garrard </PERSON> said the oldest piece in the Smithsonian show probably is a fish pendant in pure gold _ about 22 carats _ from 18th century <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION>. After the show closes at the National Museum of African Art on Aug. 28, it is scheduled to travel through July 1992 to art museums in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, Ky.
