<HEAD>Mary V. Bicouvaris, Greek Immigrant, Named Teacher of the Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts graf 4, bgng ``She is,'' with name of school</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bicouvaris </PERSON>, a Greek immigrant who survived her country's Nazi occupation and brought her perspective to high school classes in American government, was named National Teacher of the Year on Tuesday. Mrs. <PERSON> Bicouvaris </PERSON>, the 38th recipient of the award, was not even a citizen when she began teaching in <LOCATION> Hampton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, in 1963. But she became one five years later and `` developed a love for democracy that has become her teaching trademark,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> Superintendent <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Bicouvaris </PERSON>, 49, said her formula for teaching government and international relations combines `` respect for my job, love for the children that I teach, and a very sincere commitment to make a difference.'' She is a teacher at <ORGANIZATION> Bethel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hampton </LOCATION>. Known to her students as Mrs. <PERSON> Bic </PERSON>, she founded and directs an award-winning <ORGANIZATION> Model </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> program at her school and organized a schoolwide celebration of the 200th anniversary of the Constitution. Her teaching ideas on the Constitution were turned into a booklet circulated among educators nationwide. Asked if her students take citizenship seriously, Mrs. <PERSON> Bicouvaris </PERSON> said no teen-ager in any country does so. `` Our kids, they may not wave the flag. But they love this country. ... I find our kids very protective and very loving. I do n't worry about it,'' she said. But she added that `` I tell my students that I will haunt you if the day comes that it is time to vote and you do n't vote.'' In response to questions, Mrs. <PERSON> Bicouvaris </PERSON> offered advice to everyone from parents and students to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. For parents, particularly of young children, she urged them to provide a quiet place, books, love and talk, and get heavily involved in their children's schooling. `` Take the task very seriously,'' she said. `` It's like having a prize horse and developing -LRB- it -RRB- for that big race.'' For students, she said, simply `` showing up at the door of the schoolhouse'' is not enough. She also urged students to make school rather than jobs their priority during high school. `` Many students work nowadays. ... They are very busy people,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Bicouvaris </PERSON> said. `` What I find deplorable many times is they work school into the business schedule rather than fit business into the school schedule.'' For <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, scheduled to present her with a crystal apple on Wednesday, Mrs. <PERSON> Bicouvaris </PERSON> said she would ask him to follow up his pledges to be an education president with `` the action needed to make education truly a priority. ... I would like him to put the emphasis on education as an investment and not as an expense.'' The National Teacher of the Year award is sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Officers </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Encyclopaedia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Britannica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and Good Housekeeping magazine. Mrs. <PERSON> Bicouvaris </PERSON> was selected over three other finalists from <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. She will spend the next year speaking to civic groups and other organizations around the country. When Mrs. <PERSON> Bicouvaris </PERSON> was 5, her father was killed by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> occupying <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. Her uncle was rounded up with 39 other people and shot to death in retaliation for the death of a German. She came here at 20 and secured her first teaching job in her husband's home state of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> when the <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> school system waived a rule that all teachers must be American citizens. She became a citizen in 1968. Mrs. <PERSON> Bicouvaris </PERSON> said in a recent interview that surviving oppression in her Greek homeland has given her a perspective on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> government that most teachers do n't have. `` I have been fortunate to have been in two worlds,'' she said. `` I have seen how things have been when there is war, when there is oppression. It has given me a further appreciation, I believe, for freedom. It has given me a further appreciation for opportunity for all.''
