<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Beef     04-04 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Beef,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beef Shortage is Danger Sign for Brazil's Anti-Inflation Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MUELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When beef began to disappear from supermarkets last month and butchers took to the streets against illegal price increases, many Brazilians had a sinking feeling of deja vu. Three years ago, powerful cattle ranchers defied a nationwide price freeze aimed at halting runaway 1,000 percent inflation. The shortages and black marketeering that followed doomed the government's plan. Now it seemed to be happening again. The beef crisis alarmed the government. President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> called the shortage sabotage and said it threatened the fledgling democracy under which <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> on Nov. 15 will hold its first presidential election in 29 years. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> will not tolerate `` speculation, fraudulent withholding of goods -LRB- and -RRB- crimes against the economy,'' <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> said last week in a weekly nationwide radio program. `` Politicking and economic disorganization threaten the transition to democracy,'' said <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>, a civilian who took office in 1985 after 21 years of military rule. Inflation reached 28.8 percent a month in December, then fell to 3 percent for 11 days in February after the government froze prices. But the cost of living rose 6 percent in March, far above government predictions. Problems began soon after <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> on Jan. 15 announced a national wage-and-price freeze as part of his `` Summer Plan,'' <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s fourth anti-inflation program in three years Shortages soon began to occur. Eggs, auto parts and cooking oil became scarce as suppliers said they could n't meet demand at the government-set price. The government acted swiftly, negotiating a tax break for auto industries and seizing 3.8 million cans of oil in a supermarket warehouse. Federal police even detained the supermarket's owner, <PERSON> Abilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Diniz </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Pao </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acucar </ORGANIZATION> chain and one of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s wealthiest businessmen, on charges of `` crimes against the public economy. But the government was impotent against cattlemen, for centuries a powerful and independent clan in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s largest country. Cattle breeders raised the price of beef to wholesalers from $ 18 for each 32-pound unit in January to $ 23 in March. But wholesalers who tried to pass on the higher costs were fined by federal price-checkers and many simply stopped sales altogether. In many cities, butcher shops sold meat on the black market or closed their doors. Supermarkets rationed beef to customers. Butchers in cars and ox-carts marched through downtown <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s biggest city and financial center, to protest the price increases. Riot troops broke up the march with water jets colored with pink dye. The government vowed not to repeat the mistakes of 1986, when federal police on horseback and in helicopters tried to find cattle allegedly hidden in pastures. Police caught only a few cows for slaughter, and the government was ridiculed. This time, officials threatened to ban beef exports and audit the tax returns of price violators. But the ranchers did n't budge. In April, the government agreed to discuss a price increase for meat to save its anti-inflation program. Politics and inflation are closely linked in this country of 144 million. Past failed attempts to halt inflation caused the popularity of <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>'s center-right government to plummet and helped leftist parties to sharp gains in November municipal elections.
