<HEAD>Ex-Official Says He Took Money from Defense Consultants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> procurement official said Tuesday that he took thousands of dollars from defense consultants in return for providing inside information that would help private companies get military contracts. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berlin </PERSON>, who headed an aviation systems branch of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> procurement command, made the admission at the trial of three <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> executives accused of conspiring to bribe him to influence the award of an equipment contract. <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> testified that he had received at least $ 2,000 in cash from a defense consultant in return for providing detailed information about an equipment contract <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> was seeking from the Pentagon. On cross-examination, defense attorney <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuohey </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said: `` You've been selling your country short for money for 10 years?'' `` I have taken money for 10 years,'' <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> said, acknowledging receipt of thousands of dollars in payments that <PERSON> Tuohey </PERSON> listed. On direct testimony, <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> told jurors that he received two $ 1,000 cash payments, and possibly a third, from consultant <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lackner </PERSON> after providing detailed status reports about the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to buy hand-held radar test devices. <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, who pleaded guilty to charges of conspiracy and bribery last month, said he fed information to <PERSON> Lackner </PERSON> during monthly meetings they had from mid-1985 to June 1988. `` Everything I knew or could find out about the procurement was passed on to Mr. <PERSON> Lackner </PERSON>,'' <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> sai