<HEAD>Campaigns to Start Over in One-Eighth of Districts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th `Election results' with Tass report
on Leningrad meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Voters in one out of every eight Soviet parliamentary districts refused to elect anyone even though they had a choice of only one or two candidates, according to official results released Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency released the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s final tally of the votes from March 26 elections for the country's new 2,250-member <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peoples </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said that in 195 of the 1,500 geographical districts across the country, no one got a majority of the vote even though there were only one or two candidates. In those districts, new electoral campaigns will be waged and a second election will be held May 14, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Election results released earlier showed that in the first nationwide multicandidate election in 70 years voters rejected many top-ranking <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and government leaders. They included <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Solovyev </PERSON>, a candidate member of the ruling Politburo, who ran unopposed in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said a meeting of <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> party leaders Tuesday, led by <PERSON> Solovyev </PERSON>, characterized the election results as a `` serious political lesson.'' `` <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> residents are not satisfied with the tempo of solving the housing problem, the equipping of the city, the ecological situation,'' the agency said. `` They express dissatisfaction with the shortage of industrial and food products and concern about the growth of crime,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Among those who also suffered defeat were the <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> party leader and mayor, the mayor and second-leading party official in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and a host of regional party chiefs. `` In the majority of cases, the reason for this is the striving of the people to quicken the process of restructuring, more actively struggle with bureaucracy and command-administrative methods of work,'' election commission Chairman <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Orlov </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, the former <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party chief who waged an anti-establishment campaign, won his race with more than 89 percent of the vote. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> also indicated that party officials met in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> on Tuesday to review the results of the election, but no word was available on the results of that meeting. The literary weekly <ORGANIZATION> Literaturnaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION> reported that in at least one case a party leader's loss may result in a court case. The paper said the party leader of <ORGANIZATION> Alma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ata </ORGANIZATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION>, was taking his opponent to court for distributing 100,000 leaflets accusing him of selling deficit items like meat, perfume and sugar at his election rallies. V.I. <PERSON> Romanov </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Alma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ata </ORGANIZATION> party leader, lost the election to <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Safonov </PERSON>, the director of a home-building enterprise. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said two days after the balloting that party organizations would have to review the status of top officials who lost their races. He refused to characterize the vote as a defeat for the party, saying the vast majority of