<HEAD>Beirut Bombarded For Fourth Day; Americans Evacuated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian and Christian gunners traded shellfire across <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> before dawn Tuesday, bombarding the city's residential suburbs non-stop for the fourth day A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> official said two <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officers were evacuated Monday. The officers were part of a three-man technical team assigned to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> told reporters after a meeting with army commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> that, `` This fighting must stop quickly. ... It has caused tremendous damage, killed many people and brought <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s economy to its knees.'' <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> met <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> at the bunker of the battered presidential palace in suburban <LOCATION> Baabda </LOCATION>, five miles east of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> heads the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> military Cabinet in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s dual government. His 20,000 mostly Christian troops have been fighting an alliance of Syrian and Druse forces in and around <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> for the past four weeks. Police said overnight clashes killed six people and wounded 18 in Moslem and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> areas before shelling dwindled to sporadic exchanges after daybreak. The shelling began Saturday. Two more civilians were killed and seven wounded when the shelling intensified in the afteroon, said a police spokesman who can not be identified under standing rules. The latest casualties raised the toll to 155 people killed and 506 wounded since March 8, when the current round of hostilities broke out between <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s Christian troops and the Syrian and Druse Moslem fighters. Also Tuesday, Syrian soldiers allowed a convoy of four tanker trucks to cross from north <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> into the Christian hinterland northeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to provide a power station with fuel oil. <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Mawlawi </PERSON>, manager of the state oil refinery in the northern town of <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>, said the tankers would bring 1,000 tons of fuel oil for the station over the next four days. `` A total power failure would be disastrous to the whole of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Mawlawi </PERSON> said in a broadcast on the Moslem Voice of the Nation radio. Supplies were allowed in after the electricity authority warned its power station in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Zouk </PERSON> suburb would run out of fuel oil Saturday, triggering a power failure across most of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lebanon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> army gunners Monday set ablaze a Syrian army ammunition depot in the mountain resort of <LOCATION> Abadieh </LOCATION>, east of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. It said the depot `` contained lethal chemical materials which forced the Syrian army to evacuate civilians from the <LOCATION> Abadiyeh </LOCATION> area.'' The report could not be verified. Despite the relative lull that prevailed over <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and the surrounding mountains from 5 a.m., civilians remained huddled in basements and bomb shelters to avoid any sudden escalation of hostilities. A dozen families sheltering in an apartment building basement in the <LOCATION> Christian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Adonis </LOCATION> district dispatched one man to a nearby bakery. `` This is the safest way. We will send one of us to buy food for the whole building every day until a cease-fire is declared and accepted by both sides,'' <PERSON> Antoine </PERSON> <PERSON> Shedyak </PERSON>, a mechanical engineer, said by telephone. Kuwaiti Foreign Minister <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON>, head of a six-man <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> mediation committee, was due in <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> on Tuesday to try to arrange a settlement of the confrontation. The leftist daily paper As-Safir, which reflects official Syrian views, said <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> would propose a two-month truce between <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> and his opponents to give the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> committee time to work out a solution to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s six-month-old political crisis. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> has been insisting that <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> be a party to any cease-fire accord with his 20,000 troops. The Syrians, with 40,000 troops in predominantly Moslem terrritories of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> under a 1976 <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping mandate, are the main power brokers in the country. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> and other Christian leaders accuse the Syrians of failing in their mandate by siding with the Moslems against the Christians in the 14-year-old civil war. Officially, the Syrians deny their troops in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> are involved against <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s forces entrenched in the 310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The political crisis erupted Sept. 22 when President <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON>'s 6-year term expired with parliament failing to elect a successor. <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON> appointed <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Maronite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> like himself, head of an interim military cabinet to rule pending the election of a new president. Syrian-backed Moslems rejected <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s appointment because it violated a 45-year-old tradition of having a Sunni Moslem premier, a Christian president and a Shiite Moslem parliament speaker. They pledged allegiance to Acting Prime Minister <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, a Sunni who governed under <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON>.
