<HEAD>Senate Panel's S&amp;L Proposal Wins Praise, Criticism from Adminstration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A senior administration official on Tuesday praised the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s savings and loan proposal for maintaining tough capital standards, but criticized it for creating a loophole in the Gramm-Rudman budget-balancing law. The committee is meeting behind closed doors this week in preparation for public bill-writing sessions next week. On Tuesday, the panel began going over a series of changes to the administration plan proposed by the staff of the committee chairman, Sen. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Mich. According to a committee document obtained by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan would deviate only slightly from the administration's requirement that thrift owners invest more of their own money, or capital, to back up the loans they make. The administration would prevent <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls from expanding after June 1991 if they do not meet stricter capital standards. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> proposal keeps the deadline, which <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L lobbyists have been trying to push back, but would permit some weak S & amp; Ls to grow modestly even if they missed it. `` We would applaud the fact that ... they have resisted watering down the capital standards,'' Assistant Treasury Secretary <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON>, one of the key architects of the administration's proposal, said in a telephone interview Of the proposed capital changes, he said, `` I do n't see anything that's grossly out of line.'' However, he warned that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> proposal for raising $ 50 billion to close or sell failed <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls `` fundamentally threatens the Gramm-Rudman process'' by setting a precedent that could be used again for other spending programs. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has put togther a complex mechanism that combines taxpayer and industry funds and keeps the $ 50 billion out of the budget deficit by selling bonds through a quasi-government agency. <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> advocates including the spending in the budget deficit and raising the money through the sale of regular <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds, a method he says would save $ 4.5 billion over 30 years because <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds carry a lower interest rate. <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> would avoid Gramm-Rudman's automatic spending cuts by raising all of the money in the current fiscal year, now that the deficit target deadlines have passed. The administration believes its scheme for evading Gramm-Rudman ca n't be readily applied to other kinds of programs, while the <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> plan could be used every year to avoid deficit limits. <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> also warned that opposition to <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON>'s proposal from Gramm-Rudman advocates could delay passage of the entire S & amp; L package. Groups representing commercial banks are particularly happy with <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> amendments that would shift more power over S & amp; Ls to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a commercial bank regulator. The administration wants to give the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> control over the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L deposit insurance fund. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan would expand the agency's power further by giving it control over accounting and <ORGANIZATION> capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> standards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls and by making it the primary regulator of state-chartered S & amp; Ls That would leave the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L regulator, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION>, with little power. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Yingling </PERSON>, executive director of government relations for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said expanding the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION>'s control over <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls would ensure that S & amp; L standards did not become looser than bank standards. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Guenther </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, said he was pleased by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> change that would give the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> chairman a set term. The administration wants the president to have the power to dismiss the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> chairman at will. `` We think Sen. <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> has moved very much in the right direction in terms of making the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> board considerly more independent of the White House and <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. We think that's a major plus,'' <PERSON> Guenther </PERSON> said.
