<BYLINE>By WILLIAM E. SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gen. <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, the former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> security adviser, said Tuesday that despite turmoil in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, that country's armed forces were strong and ready to fight. <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> was installed as head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> and said his job was to keep 1 million active, reserve and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> troops in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> ready for combat `` with the hope they will never be needed.'' `` The Soviets are going through wrenching historic change, beginning with the irreversible acknowledgement that their system is broken and has to be changed,'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said at a ceremony at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> McPherson </LOCATION>, the headquarters of the command, which is known as FORSCOM. Despite the Soviets' internal turmoil, `` there is nothing wrong with their deployed forces,'' he said. `` Their FORSCOM is strong. We must be strong.'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said a priority was <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and reserve units, which `` are not as ready as we would like them to be. We do n't have the resources.'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said he saw a role for the military in the war on drugs, but cautioned against its use as a police force. `` I will not be resistant to finding ways for the military to help civilian authorities in defense against a major threat,'' he said. `` I think there are opportunities for our men to get good training'' in interdiction. <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> cautioned that even an apparently innovative leader like <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <P