<HEAD>D.C. Police Could Arrest Those Loitering in Illegal Drug Zones</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The District of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> approved an emergency anti-loitering bill Tuesday that would give the city's police power to arrest people congregating in designated `` illegal drug zones. The bill, the latest move in the city's attempt to curb drug-related violence, allows police to make arrests if those gathering in a such a zone refuse to move on when asked to do so. The mayor has 10 days in which to sign the measure, which then would be effective for 90 days. The police chief would be able to designate a place with a history of drug activity over six months as an illegal drug zone and to ban congregation in an area of 1,000 square feet for up to 120 hours. The areas, limited to public property such as sidewalks, streets, and public-housing courtyards, would be clearly marked by signs, barriers and police tape. The maximum penalty for loitering would be $ 300 or 90 days in jail. `` The intent of the bill is to be able to disperse people,'' said <PERSON> Nadine </PERSON> <PERSON> Winter </PERSON>, a member of the council. `` We recognize that we will have to impede on the rights of others in order for us to gain control of our community,'' said H.R. <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, another council member. He said he feared residents of neighborhoods where drug sales are rampant will be subject to arrest whnever they gather outdoors. `` These areas are non-air-conditioned public housing units. When it gets hot, of course, people are going to come outside,'' he said. Council Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> assured <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> the measure only prohibits congregating if police have asked the people to move on.
