<HEAD>Survey Finds Fire Ants Send 21,000 To Doctor Yearly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fire ant stings send at least 21,000 people a year to doctors in 13 Southern states, a survey has found. The survey of physicians for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allergy </ORGANIZATION> and Immunology also found that 413 people were treated for life-threatening reactions to fire ant stings last year and that 32 died, most of them because they were hypersensitive to the ant's poison In most of those who died, the ant stings triggered an anaphylactic or allergic response which caused the body's respiratory system to shut down `` People and physicians should take these stings seriously,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhoades </PERSON>, a pediatrician at the <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION>. People who are allergic to other kinds of insect stings should be especially cautious, said <PERSON> Rhoades </PERSON>, who heads a special panel that monitors medical problems caused by fire ants. Fire ants arrived in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> by boat from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and have been slowly moving northward and westward. Cold weather has seemingly confined them to the Deep South. But recent studies have shown the ant is crossbreeding and that the hybrid, which can withstand lower temperatures, may push its range farther north into the north <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> mountains and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. More than 2,000 physicians in 13 states, or about 10 percent of those polled, responded to the allergy academy survey, indicating they treat about 21,000 patients a year for fire ant stings. Most of those stung were treated successfully with over-the-counter antihistamines.
