<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The governments of the Greek and <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> communities have agreed to withdraw their soldiers from three tense observation points on the Green Line in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, officials said Tuesday. <PERSON> Rauf </PERSON> <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON>, president of the breakaway <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, confirmed in an interview that his government had fully agreed with the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plan for the pullback. The agreement in principle marks the first time the Cypriot government and the administration of the <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> have ever concluded a military withdrawal agreement, said officials from both communities. Greek Cypriot troops are only 10 yards from Turkish Cypriot troops at some points in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>. In 1988, a Turkish Cypriot and a <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> were killed in separate sniping attacks across the Green Line, as the unofficial buffer zone dividing the two ethnic communities is known. Under the terms of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plan, both the Greek and Turkish Cypriot forces will withdraw from the posts, but will not necessarily have to dismantle their defense works, said a Turkish Cypriot official, speaking on condition of anonymity. Cypriot Defense Minister <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Aloneftis </PERSON> said his government has agreed to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plan. Both sides still have to sign formal documents with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. If the plan succeeds, <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON> said, it would `` naturally'' lead to further steps toward demilitarization, `` provided the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> is between us. Our armed people must not see each other from different points.'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peacekeeping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, known as <ORGANIZATION> UNFICYP </ORGANIZATION>, was established in 1964. Since 1974, it has patrolled the Green Line in an attempt to defuse hostilities. It has about 2,100 troops and 34 police monitors from nine nations. <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> are in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for a third round of talks mediated by Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> on how to reconcile the Greek and Turkish communities on <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON> said Tuesday he has little hope the talks will result in progress toward reunifying the divided island. The <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island has been unofficially partitioned since the Greek government fomented a coup and Turkish troops moved into the northern sector in 1974 to protect the Turkish minority community. The coup failed, but about 30,000 Turkish troops remain and about 50,000 Turks moved from the mainland to settle in northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON>'s government demands the removal of the Turkish troops and settlers as part of the process of establishing a national republic with two states with virtual autonomy in local affairs. <PERSON> Dentash </PERSON>'s Turkish Cypriot community declared itself a nation in 1983, but has only been recognized by <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. The Turkish Republic covers about 37 percent of northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, and has 120,000 residents, mostly Moslems. They form about 18 percent of the entire population of the island.
