<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Silence Town Bell That Keeps Couple Awake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTHAMPTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> town clock can keep on chiming at night despite a couple's lawsuit charging that it keeps them awake, a judge ruled. Superior Court Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said, in rejecting a request for a temporary injunction Monday, that silencing the clock until trial `` will not best serve the public's interest.'' The judge also said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> Carnall </PERSON> failed to show they would suffer irreparable harm if the clock was allowed to continue to toll the hours. The Carnalls, who moved to the little farming community of 3,200 people last summer when the 200-year-old clock was not working, sued last month after selectmen declined to shut off the clock at night. The couple contends the clock, located in the steeple of the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congregational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> about 50 feet from their home, booms the hours at 75 decibels, 15 decibels louder than a vacuum cleaner and 25 decibels above the level the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has set as the loudest people can sleep through. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said in his decision that expert testimony would be required at trial to determine decibel levels as well as the mechanical feasibility of installing a timer to shut off the chimes late at night. The Carnalls were away from home and could not be reached for comment Tuesday. But their attorney, <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, said he would seek to bring the case to trial as quickly as possible. `` Most people are sympathetic to the <LOCATION> Carnalls </LOCATION>, even people who want the bell to keep ringing,'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> contended.
