<FIRST>r w AM-OilSpills-Chemicals     04-04 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spills-Chemicals,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says Chemicals Of Limited Value In Major Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chemical agents such as those applied in response to the vast oil spill in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Prince </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> William </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sound </ORGANIZATION> are of limited value in major spills but can be effective in dispersing smaller slicks, according to a study published Tuesday. The study by a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> panel of academic and industry experts said use of dispersants generally is helpful in ocean spills but more biological studies are needed to determine how coastal habitats are affected by the chemicals. The research council is an independent adviser to the government on scientific issues. Its study was conducted before last month's spill of 10 million gallons of crude oil from the Exxon Valdez, the largest in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history Dispersants are most effective when applied to oil within the first five hours after a spill, the study said, adding that a day or two of evaporation and weathering cause spilled oil to become too thick to disperse with chemicals. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s application of a dispersant called Corexit was delayed for more than a day, first because the water was too cold and calm, then because strong winds that created a better environment for the dispersants hampered the aircraft used to spread the chemicals. `` Applying dispersants quickly is especially important because effective alternatives do not exist for treating ocean oil spills,'' the council report said. Dispersants usually are made of thick liquid detergent that is mixed with a solvent that thins the detergent and makes it easier to apply. The molecules of the dispersant attach themselves to the oil, reducing the surface tension between the oil and the water. This makes it easier for the oil to dissolve in the water. The report quoted <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, chairman of the experts panel, as saying, `` The mandate is clear to use chemical dispersants'' when oil must be dispersed before it reaches shore. Once oil enters coastal habitats, the decision to use chemicals is more difficult, the study said, since fish and shellfish can be harmed. For years, chemical dispersants have been suspected by some of causing more environmental harm than good. The research council report said experts who studied a 1967 oil spill off <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in which thousands of tons of dispersants were used concluded that the chemicals contributed to the deaths of local animals and plants.
</TEXT>
