has controlled for 74 years. South African military officials say the fighting is the heaviest since the 1966 start of the <PERSON> bush </PERSON> war against <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>. South African <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> television showed bodies of more than a dozen guerrillas killed in one clash. Journalists toured northern <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> and saw evidence of heavy fighting, but casualty figures could not be independently confirmed. <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> and other <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> officials say the guerrillas were in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> for some time and that South African-led forces initiated the fighting. `` Our people have been fighting inside <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> in the past 20 years,'' <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> told reporters after meeting in <LOCATION> Harare </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, with representatives from the the five permanent member nations of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> said he planned to end two decades of exile and return to <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> `` very soon.'' He asked the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to bolster its cease-fire monitoring forces in northern <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> authorized 4,650 troops for the <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> operation, but only about 1,000 have arrived and no more than 300 are in northern <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> forces made no effort to i