<HEAD>Students Protesting Economic Measures Battle Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Students protesting government austerity measures battled police Tuesday. Officials said one demonstrator and a policeman were injured and 30 people were arrested. Police reinforcements rushed to <LOCATION> Catia </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> suburb, when hundreds of youths began burning tires after bus drivers refused to give students a 50 percent fare discount authorized by a government decree. A police spokesman said of the injured: `` The policeman was shot in a leg with a projectile and the student sustained several injuries from plastic shotgun pellets.'' Students outside the <ORGANIZATION> Caracas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Venezuela </ORGANIZATION> later seized a bus and set it on fire. No casualties or arrests were reported. In <LOCATION> Maracaibo </LOCATION>, 300 miles west of <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, most university and public high school classes were suspended Tuesday, the day after students burned a bus and a police truck. The Maracaibo protesters also said bus drivers were not allowing the discount for students and were charging them full fare. Demonstrations have been frequent since the government began applying in February the provisions of an economic package approved by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. Bus fares were increased, but the government earmarked $ 10 million to subsidize the 50 percent discount for students. Transport companies said the reduced fares did n't cover their expenses. More than 300 people were killed in riots that erupted Feb. 27 to protest price increases. Most of the deaths were in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, where about 3,000 stores were looted. President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>' Social Democratic administration has continued to imple