<SECOND>AM-Caribou Return,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woodland Caribou Return to Maine Wilds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GLENN ADAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILLINOCKET, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tranquilized caribou were loaded onto a van Tuesday and carried north toward their new home in the wilderness under a plan to restore the reindeer-like animal in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. Six to eight caribou, some weighing as much as 250 pounds, were to be taken to <LOCATION> Baxter </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, a 200,000-acre wilderness preserve. After being shot with tranquilizer guns, the ungainly creatures were lifted on canvas stretchers and carried onto a van for the 70-mile journey. Blindfolded to reduce stress, they were placed side by side on a bed of straw. Scientists hope the animals will use their new home as a breeding ground. <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>'s once-abundant caribou were wiped out in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> by overhunting and disease. The last native woodland caribou to be seen in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> was spotted in 1908 on mile-high <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Katahdin </LOCATION> in the park's southern end. Dr. <PERSON> Ladd </PERSON> <PERSON> Heldenbrand </PERSON>, a veterinarian monitoring the animals, was optimistic about the animals' chances of flourishing in the wild. The biggest threats to the caribou are parasites and predators, <PERSON> Heldenbrand </PERSON> said. `` We hope the public is educated enough to leave them alone,'' he said. `` They're the public's animals. We hope they will respect them.'' Release of the 1 - and 2-year-old caribou caps a two-year effort begun in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> Biologists and state officials in 1986 had more than two dozen rounded up in <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> and trucked 1,200 miles to the University of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. Calves born since then will be the nucleus of the new herd. By Wednesday, officials hoped to have transported 14 of the docile, tan animals to Baxter State Park, officials said. The animals will be fitted with radio collars so scientists can keep track of them and determine whether they are being pursued by coyotes and bears, said biologist <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> McCollough </PERSON>, director of the privately funded project.
