<SECOND>AM-Base Closings,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBO: Base Savings Said Too High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal commission that recommended shutting down 86 military bases and partly closing five more was optimistic in its assessment that the move will save $ 5.6 billion over 20 years, a congressional budget official said Tuesday. `` The commission's estimates of savings fell at the upper end of the range suggested by our data,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hale </PERSON>, assistant director at the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee. `` Unfortunately, missing historical data and differences in definitions make comparisons of one-time costs and savings unclear.'' The commission did not include the cost of federal economic assistance in estimating the plan's savings but did include the expected revenues from sale of the land presently used by the bases, <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> said. However, the office's analysis found that of the 33 bases closed during the 1970s, the government only got 35 percent of the fair-market value for sale of the land. In some cases, the property was donated for educational use and other public services. The commission estimated savings of $ 694 million a year, with 20-year savings estimated at $ 5.6 billion. `` Based on the historic data, they were optimistic ... not wildly so,'' <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations subcommittees on defense and military construction. Lawmakers expressed concerns about the commission's recommendations at two separate <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearings while acknowledging the plan will likely go into effect next month and base closings will begin in 1990 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> can block the proposal, which former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> approved in January, but the chances are unlikely. The House Armed Services panel voted 43-4 last month to support the commission's recommendations to close 86 facilities, partially close five others and change the mission in 54 other installations. The full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is expected to follow suit later this month. Nevertheless, legislators held hearings to question the planned closing of some of their local bases. At the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on readiness, sustainability and support, Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, D-Ill., cited recently unclassified transcripts of the commission's meetings in which members discussed time constraints that prohibited a more extensive examination of available data on each base <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> argued against the planned closing of <ORGANIZATION> Chanute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, near <LOCATION> Champaign </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, and railed against the rating system the commission used to make its decision. `` Who was the mother, father or brainchild of the rating system,'' <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> asked. `` A lot of people on the commission staff,'' responded Dr. <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, executive director of the commission staff. Seated behind <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> were 10 members of his staff and <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> called on each one to stand and give their name. The <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> senator also asked the staff members to write down their names and addresses. `` The commission gave responsibility to faceless people,'' <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> said. In defense of the commission's decision, <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> noted the base closing was `` recommended by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, chartered by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.''
