<FIRST>u w AM-Abortion-Justice     04-04 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Justice,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Attorneys Protest Abortion Position</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 200 <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attorneys submitted a petition Tuesday to Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> criticizing the department's attempt to persuade the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to overturn the landmark 1973 decision legalizing abortion. `` We believe that every woman has the right to make her own decision about whether or not to continue her pregnancy in accordance with the guidelines set forth in <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>,'' the petition said, referring to the 1973 case. `` We oppose any governmental interference with this basic right.'' The petition bearing 248 names, most of them attorneys, was given to <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s office late in the afternoon, according to one of the signers. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON>, a top aide to <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, said the petition `` wo n't have any impact on the department's position. `` These people come in six months after the decision was made to appeal this case to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. `` It's not timely. ... If they wanted to have an impact on what the department was doing on this, they're six months too late.'' One of the signers, an attorney who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said the petition was submitted late because attorneys at the department are very busy and it took a long time to get the organization in motion. In addition, she said the signers hope the petition will make an impact on other cases. She said <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> and the department had involved themselves in partisan politics by intervening in the case. <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said he did n't expect any retaliation against the people who signed the petition, saying, `` The attorney general understands this is a controversial issue that people disagree on.'' `` I do n't anticipate any impact ... unless people decide that they so disagree that they can no longer work here,'' he said. The case before the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is called <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> vs. Reproductive Health Services, and it concerns a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> law that prohibits the use of public funds or public employees from `` encouraging'' or `` performing'' or `` assisting'' an abortion. The 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> rejected key portions of the law last July 13. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> could act on the <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> case without touching the 1973 <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> decision, but the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, in a brief filed in February, urged the court to overturn its earlier ruling and leave decisions on abortions to legislators. The signer who commented on the petition said the majority of those who signed are women. She said the many female attorneys at Justice give the issue relevance, serving as reminders that their ability to pursue careers would be compromised by unwanted pregnancies. <PERSON> Colleen </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> praised the employees who signed the petition. `` Quite apart from the issue of what the department is doing on <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, it's heartening to know there are a few government lawyers willing to exercise their First Amendment rights,'' she said. `` The attorney general obviously can respond any way he wants to that petition, but he of all people has to know that his employees should not bear any recriminations for expressing their views on an issue as important as this one,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
