<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eighteen months after it was convicted of selling bogus apple juice to consumers, the <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has been debarred from doing any business with the federal government through 1991. The corporation, suspended from federal contracting since December 1986, is now being debarred `` to protect the government's interest in doing business only with contractors who conduct business with honesty and integrity,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s order states The debarment, which <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> contested, was announced Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Logistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. The company was advised of the decision in a letter dated March 3, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> added. A suspension is normally the first step toward a company either being debarred or allowed to resume bidding on government work. A contract debarment is the harshest administrative sanction the Pentagon can impose on a contractor. Such an order, whose term can vary, prevents a company from bidding on or receiving any new contract from any agency of the federal government _ not just the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. In <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION>'s case, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> announced in January it was changing the suspension of the <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nutrition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a wholly owned subsidiary, to a debarment. By taking the same action Tuesday against the parent <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the Pentagon has barred any and all units of the corporation from receiving any government contract `` through Dec. 4, 1991.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nutrition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> was convicted Nov. 13, 1987, in federal court in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on a total of 215 counts involving charges of introducing adulterated food into commerce and violating the federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act. `` The criminal conduct of Beech-Nut Nutrition involved manufacturing juice for babies which was labeled as and represented to be pure apple juice, but in fact contained little, if any, apple or fruit juice,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> noted in its order. The financial impact of Tuesday's action on the company appears slight. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Logistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> purchases Beech-Nut products for resale in military commissaries around the world. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> DLA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said he could not immediately estimate the value of the government's business to the company before it was suspended in 1986. Other Pentagon officials said, however, the total was well below $ 1 million a year. Nonetheless, the company had strongly fought the debarment action since being advised of the possibility last December, arguing an entirely new management team had taken over and any damage that had been incurred had been incurred by consumers and not the federal government. `` The government bought the juice for resale to military members and their families in commissaries,'' countered <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Werfel </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> DLA </ORGANIZATION>'s special assistant for contracting integrity, in the debarment order. `` The government paid for 100 percent pure apple juice, received artificial juice, and government employees were offered the artificial juice while assuming that the juice was 100 percent pure applie juice. To say that the government was not damaged in these circumstances is further evidence of <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION>'s continuing lack of responsibility.'' <PERSON> Werfel </PERSON> added the evidence was clearly sufficient to show that `` the <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> was and is responsible for the actions of <ORGANIZATION> Beech-Nut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nutrition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, including its criminal activity from December 1981 through March 1983.'' Beech-Nut, which is headquartered in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said it found the <ORGANIZATION> DLA </ORGANIZATION>'s action `` inexplicable.'' `` It is beyond question that our products today are authentic, pure and safe,'' added a company spokesman, who asked not to be named. `` This happened nearly six years ago, and stringent quality control programs were put in place by the new management. We are puzzled by this move and find it inexplicable that <ORGANIZATION> DLA </ORGANIZATION> is impugning the current management by this action.''
</TEXT>
