<HEAD>SWAPO Guerrilla Chief Vows To Return To Namibia Soon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Namibian guerrilla chief <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> vowed Tuesday he would shortly return to his homeland, scene of the bloodiest clashes between security forces and guerrillas in 23 years of war. His return would effectively end more than two decades as an exile, wanted by the South African rulers of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> as a terrorist. But aides said it would not be his first visit home. `` He has been in and out with his men quite often,'' said one official, who spoke on condition of not being identified. <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> addressed a news conference after he urged the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to immediately bolster its cease-fire monitoring forces in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. Asked if he would be going to <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> replied, `` Yes, very soon.'' <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> reiterated denials that 1,200 of his men infiltrated <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> in violation of the cease-fire accord, insisting `` our people have been fighting inside <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> in the past 20 years.'' He said that in his 90-minute talks Tuesday with mission chiefs of the five permament <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> members _ <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> _ he expressed `` utter disgust over the killing of innocent Namibians, some of whom were celebrating the start of the cease-fire.'' A cease-fire is the initial stage of an independence transition period for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, a onetime German colony ruled for the last 74 years by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, said he urged the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> through the envoys to stop the South African-led security forces `` from butchering Namibians and confine the South African army to their barracks.'' He described as `` full-scale war'' the fighting that first broke out last Saturday, the day the cease-fire was to go into effect. The combat has killed 169 of his fighters, 19 police and one South African soldier. Meeting with <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> were <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Charge d'Affaires <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Fugat </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> while appointment of a new ambassador is awaited; British High Commissioner -LRB- ambassador -RRB- <PERSON> Ramsay </PERSON> <PERSON> Melhuish </PERSON>; and ambassadors <PERSON> Arrkadi </PERSON> <PERSON> Gloukhou </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, Song Ghoqing of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Garriague-Guyonnaud </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON>, who directs <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> from exile in the Angolan capital of <LOCATION> Luanda </LOCATION>, is expected to discuss the crisis this week with leaders of the so-called Front-line states _ black African nations that border on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> or are particularly concerned with events there. That regional bloc _ <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tanzania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> _ spearheads African efforts to end <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s policy of apartheid, or racial segregation. Front-line leaders often expressed fears <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> would try to sabotage moves towards Namibian independence. <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> is in <LOCATION> Harare </LOCATION> for a three-day meeting on <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> of 150 legislators from the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> European Parliamentarians against Apartheid.
