<HEAD>California Panel To Issue Appeal Ruling On Spiro Agnew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A state board is expected to rule later this week whether former Vice President <PERSON> Spiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON> can get a refund on his <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> taxes for money he had to pay to <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> as restitution in a kickback case. <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON> is appealing a 1986 denial by the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Franchise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> of his request for a refund of $ 24,197. <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON>, who pleaded no contest to corruption charges and resigned as vice president in 1973, paid $ 142,000 in restitution for allegedly accepting bribes from road engineering contractors while he was governor of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> from 1967 to 1969. The former vice president views the court-ordered restitution as an expenditure and wants to recover a percentage of it, said <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bertane </PERSON>, senior counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equalization </ORGANIZATION>, the appellate panel. The board's ruling will be issued Thursday, the attorney said. `` It's fairly routine. It does n't present any extremely novel legal questions,'' <PERSON> Bertane </PERSON> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON> originally sought the deduction on his 1981 tax return, filed after he became a resident of Rancho Mirage and just months after he made restitution. The Franchise <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 rejected the deduction because `` <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> has never received any income, in the form of taxes or otherwise, from the amounts -LRB- <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON> -RRB- allegedly received as bribes.'' To approve the deduction, the board said, would have the effect of requiring <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> taxpayers to subsidize <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON>'s `` return of public monies to the taxpayers of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, urged the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equalization </ORGANIZATION> to `` ignore the identity of those involved.''
