<HEAD>Paper Says Imelda Will Embalm Marcos for Display</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> says she will embalm her husband's body when he dies and display it in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> until she can return and scatter his ashes to `` fertilize'' the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, a newspaper reported Tuesday. `` Not only will it be a political statement: It will be a spectacle _ an international spectacle to have <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> -LRB- lie is state -RRB- here,'' she told <ORGANIZATION> BusinessWorld </ORGANIZATION> in an interview at the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> home in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> over the weekend. President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, his family and several cronies fled to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> when a military-civilian uprising in February 1986 put <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> in power. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, 71, has been hospitalized in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> since Jan. 15 with heart and lung ailments. Hospital officials say he remains in guarded condition. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has repeatedly rejected requests that the former president be allowed to return. Cabinet Secretary <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> said in February the president and <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> had agreed, for security reasons, that not even his body would be allowed into the country. The paper quoted Mrs. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> as saying: `` I'll keep <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> here until 1992, then I'll bring him home.'' President <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s term ends in that year. In May, <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' mother died at age 95, and her body was embalmed and put on display. Relatives say they are waiting to bury <PERSON> Josefa </PERSON> <PERSON> Edralin-Marcos </PERSON> until the former president returns. Her body lies in state at the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> home in <LOCATION> Batac </LOCATION>, 240 miles north of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. A mortician visits every two months to inject embalming fluid and retouch the makeup on her face. <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was quoted as expressing optimism that Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s successor would let them return and fulfill a wish of her husband to be cremated and have his ashes scattered `` to fertilize his country.'' She is more than 20 years younger than her husband and once was groomed to succeed him, but the paper quoted her as saying she had no intention of running for the presidency in 1992. `` I've seen it all,'' she said. `` I've had it all. Now all I want is to be left alone.'' The Marcoses have been indicted on racketeering charges by a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> grand jury. Mrs. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> pleaded innocent at her arraignment last October but the former president's arraignment has been postponed because of his health. They are accused of stealing more than $ 100 million of public funds and using it to buy real estate in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The Aquino government says the Marcoses and their associates plundered at least $ 10 billion during his 20 years in power.
