<HEAD>Peruvian Jetliner Crashes On Landing, 11 People Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with company saying 11, sted 14,
injured and 137 aboard; company version of accident. Pickup 10th pvs, `In
Seattle...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Peruvian jetliner carrying 137 people crashed and burst into flames as it landed at a jungle airport, injuring 11 passengers and crew members, <ORGANIZATION> Faucett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday. It said the others escaped unharmed. The privately owned airline said the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 crashed at 6:43 p.m. Monday at the airport in <LOCATION> Iquitos </LOCATION>, 715 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, during a heavy rainstorm. It said the craft skidded off the edge of the runway, a landing gear and the right wing broke off and fire broke out. The pilot and co-pilot were among the 11 injured, all of whom were Peruvians, according to <ORGANIZATION> Faucett </ORGANIZATION>. It said most of the injuries were minor but two people were hospitalized. The government's <ORGANIZATION> Andina </ORGANIZATION> news agency said earlier 130 people were aboard the jet and 14 were injured, suffering second-degree burns or hurt when they leaped to safety as flames engulfed the plane. It said some of the people jumped from the plane even before it came to a halt. <ORGANIZATION> Andina </ORGANIZATION>'s account gave a slightly different version of the accident. It said the airliner tilted sideways when it was about 1,500 feet from the runway and one engine exploded in flames. The nose of the craft rammed into the runway and both wings tore off as the plane skidded along the tarmac, according to <ORGANIZATION> Andina </ORGANIZATION>. It said the flames destroyed the fuselage, but <LOCATION> Iquitos </LOCATION> airport officials reported the fire damage to the fuselage was minor. The airport officials also said the fire broke out after the plane had landed and went out of control. <ORGANIZATION> Andina </ORGANIZATION> said there had been no indications that the jetliner, Flight 302 en route to <LOCATION> Iquitos </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, had encountered earlier difficulties. Airport officials blamed the crash on `` unfavorable climatic conditions and strong tropical rains.'' In <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> said the company had not received any direct information on the crash. He said the company and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> could send observers for any investigation if invited by Peruvian authorities. <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> the agency has not received a request from <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> concerning the accident and would not become involved unless invited to participate. In the last serious accident of a jetliner in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> 12 people were killed when an airliner of state-owned Aeroperu crashed on takeoff in October in the city of <LOCATION> Puno </LOCATION>, 610 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>. On March 10, eight <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> tourists and two crew members perished when a British-made twin-engined plane crashed into a two-story university building in a <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> suburb.
