<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrats were favored to hold an <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> congressional seat in a special election Tuesday that amounted to a test run for Republicans hoping to gain ground in the Deep South in 1990. Secretary of State <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Browder </PERSON>, the Democratic nominee, faced a lesser-known Republican foe, state Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Opelika </LOCATION>, in a roughhouse, name-calling race for the 3rd Congressional District seat. The seat was left vacant in December with the death of Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON>, a conservative Democrat from <LOCATION> Sylacauga </LOCATION> who held the mostly rural, 13-county east <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> district for 22 years. The district, which is about 75 percent white and dotted with small towns, appeared ready-made for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>'s plan to bring such conservative-leaning Southern seats into the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> column next year. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> captured over 60 percent of the district's votes last November. But Democrats sought a second straight off-year special election victory over Republicans.
