<TEXT>
 Two weeks ago, Democrat <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON> won an <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> congressional seat that once was held by Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and was viewed as a GOP stronghold. A third off-year congressional election will be held April 26 in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> to fill <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON>'s House seat. <PERSON> Browder </PERSON>, 46, a former political science professor at <ORGANIZATION> Jacksonville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, was strongly supported by blacks and organized labor. He has a reputation as an election reform advocate and was endorsed by all six daily newspapers that circulate in the district. <PERSON> Browder </PERSON> is from <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, but lives outside the district in <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, 37, a real estate developer from <LOCATION> Opelika </LOCATION> who switched parties last year after getting elected to the legislature as a Democrat, pinned his hopes on a campaign strategy of relentlessly labeling <PERSON> Browder </PERSON> as a liberal. Gov. <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'s first Republican governor this century, toured the district regularly on behalf of <LOCATION> Rice </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Browder </PERSON> ran television spots calling <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> a `` hand grenade'' who had taken potentially explosive stands to cut federal aid to the elderly in half while voting to raise his legislative salary by 50 percent. <PERSON> Browder </PERSON> also called <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> an `` off-the-wall radical.'' <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> countered by calling <PERSON> Browder </PERSON> `` a wimp ... a liberal ... a liar.'' <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>'s campaign received heavy financial support from national