<DATELINE>COVINGTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Divers pulled a car from the <LOCATION> Hatchie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> on Tuesday and recovered from it the body of an eighth victim of a weekend bridge collapse that may have been caused by flood damage. Four state inspection teams fanned out across western <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> to check other bridges for weather damage. State Transportation Commissioner <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said heavy spring floods after two years of drought probably contributed to the collapse Saturday night by washing sandy soil away from the bridge supports. `` We're trying to make sure there's nothing that we have overlooked in this area,'' he said. The body found Tuesday in a gray compact station wagon was not immediately identified. Seven other victims were recovered earlier. Crews searching the flooded river earlier in the day discovered signs of a possible fifth vehicle lost when a 90-foot section of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 51 bridge gave way. A dog trained to smell bodies buried in rubble or under water pointed searchers to a section of the river adjacent to the accident on Monday. The object's position was confirmed Tuesday by a boat crew using a magnet, and a wrecker pulled the car out in the afternoon. Crews also set up a crane to lift away the concrete slabs covering at least three other cars and a tractor-trailer. Workers had used jackhammers since the accident to break up the three slabs into pieces small enough to be raised by the crane. State officials said the collapse about 50 miles north of <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> may have been caused by flood waters washing out the soil around the bridge supports. The span that collapsed was 55 years old and carried two lanes of northbound traffic. The adjacent bridge, which carried southbound traffic, was not damaged but has been closed.
