<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<HEAD>Petition Calling For Amnesty Given To Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A petition calling for the release of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s political prisoners and signed by 24,000 people was given to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s legislature a week after it was seized by customs officers, state media said Tuesday The official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said customs officials in <LOCATION> Tianjin </LOCATION> forwarded the petition to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, which closed its annual session Tuesday. The petition was seized last Tuesday from a group of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> human rights activists who were attempting to bring it into <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. A day later, the activists brought their case to the legislature and requested that the petition be forwarded to the congress. <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> quoted a spokesman of the <LOCATION> Tianjin </LOCATION> customs office as saying the request had been granted `` to respect the right of those <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> compatriots who took part in the signing to express their views and suggestions.'' The official said other materials seized, such as magazines and pro-democracy periodicals, would not be released. The petition was signed by 24,163 people. Most of the signatories were Chinese from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and the West, but people from 34 other countries also participated. The petition demanded specifically that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> release <PERSON> Wei </PERSON> <PERSON> Jingsheng </PERSON>, serving a 15-year sentence for `` counterrevolutionary'' crimes. <PERSON> Wei </PERSON> was arrested 10 years ago after he called for democracy. A growing number of intellectuals in Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> are calling for an amnesty f