<HEAD>Daley Never Wandered Far From Early Political Arena</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chicago Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 His nickname in high school was `` Mayor'' and his traffic ticket on a trip home from college made front-page news. Few men are to the manor born, but <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, almost everyone said, was born to be mayor. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> realized that destiny when he was elected to the office his father held for 21 years. Throughout a political career that had its beginnings nearly 30 years ago, the <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> name made many of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON>'s achievements possible, diminished others, and left him forever open to the charge that his vision extends only as far as his father's shadow. He lived at home until he was 30, and now, at age 46, still lives only a few blocks from the bungalow where he grew up in the working-class <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION> neighborhood. He looks, walks, talks, and occasionally misspeaks in a way that makes him unmistakeably the son of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, the late six-term <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> mayor and big-city boss. `` He even began to look more like his father in recent weeks,'' said <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Loyola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor. `` He was chunkier, more confident, he gave the same monosyllabic answers with a lot of common sense in them.'' The most frequent criticism of the younger <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> is that he has the same politics as his father and will revive the <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> `` Machine.'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, author of `` Himself,'' a biography of the elder <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, said he did n't think that was true. `` For one thing, a ` Machine' like the old man's is a political dinosaur that will never again roam the earth,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said, also noting <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s unsuccessful 1983 mayoral bid chastened him. The eldest son of seven children, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> cut his political teeth working as an 18-year-old page for the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> delegation to the 1960 Democratic National Convention. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> graduated from law school in 1968. His father rewarded him with a job as an assistant corporation counsel after he passed the bar exam on his third try. The elder <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> also slated his son for a seat in the Illinois Constitutional Convention. Then, in 1972, his father sent old <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> machine warhorse <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Nihill </PERSON> packing and virtually handed <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> his seat in the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The younger <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> was criticized in his early years, called little more `` his father's eyes and ears,'' and `` dirty little <PERSON> Richie </PERSON>'' by one colleague for using his chairmanship of the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to routinely squash good-government legislation. But many of those same colleagues recalled how two events changed him irrevocably. The first came on Dec. 20, 1976, when his father died months into a sixth term. A year and a half later, his third child, <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON>, was born with the crippling disease spina bifida. `` After Dad died, <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> looked at himself for the first time without Dad looking over his shoulder,'' recalled <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s brother <PERSON> Bill </PERSON>, his chief political strategist and the youngest of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>.'s seven children. The strain of <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON>'s illness may have an equally profound impact on his life. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> began taking a leadership role in such legislative issues as nursing homes and abolishing taxes on some foods and medicine. He showed a political acumen few thought him capable of, and forged cautious alliances with the same reformers who often had opposed his father. As a result, when he ran for the first of his three terms as <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> state's attorney in 1980, Democrats slated <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> to run against him. The younger <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> clobbered <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, then twice won re-election.
