y Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> described the 90-minute private meeting as `` very beneficial and fruitful'' but said commitments on the aid issue were neither sought nor given. Both <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> said senators told the Egyptian president that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must keep the large <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> budget deficit in mind in dealing with all requests for economic and military assistance. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said senators appeared favorably impressed with <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON>'s description of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s economic reform program, including the reduction of subsidies on a number of consumer products and revisions in the country's tax structure. `` The president argued that the pace he is pursuing is the one most appropriate to their circumstances and the one most likely to bring success,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. The Egyptian leader is hoping that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will approve new weapons sales once they are formally proposed by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration and that $ 230 million in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic aid will be released. The aid was withheld in March pending reforms in the way <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> manages its economy which that country must have in place by June. Meanwhile, 200 American Jews said in a statement released by Tikkum magazine in <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, that they challenged <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s policies and urged him to begin negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> `` Many American Jews, loyal supporters of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, do not support the suppression of the Palestinian people and the continued occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>,'' the statement said. `` You do not have a blank check from American Jewry to continue these policies.'' Tikkum is a bimonthly magazine that concentrates on political and cultural issues of special interest to American Jews. The signers included the comedian and writer <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, novelist <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, playwright <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and civil rights lawyer <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Raugh </PERSON>. `` Begin negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>,'' the statement said. `` Not only has the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> begun to talk to talk with them but recent polls indicate that 58 percent of American Jews would support direct negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> leaders. `` If you are serious about seeking peace, you must be prepared to talk directly with your enemies, and you can not expect to pick their representatives for them.'' In a toast at a White House dinner honoring <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said called his two days of meetings with <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> `` productive, a time for seeking common ground in approaching the peace process as well as a good time to discuss the bilateral issues.'' `` I firmly believe that peace will prevail if we continue to work with a common purpose in the spirit of teamwork,'' he said. `` We must work to create a new atmosphere for Palestinians and Israelis to put aside violence in favor of words. A dialogue for peace for peace is the best way to establish <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> security and give the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> their legitimate political rights.'' <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON>, in his toast, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s presidency ushers `` a new era of our freindship and cooperation,'' and called the president `` a great 