<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>LOD, Israel: mixed neighborhood</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Do the Rantisis expect to return to Lod? Are they willing to compromise and settle for a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state limited to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>? Would they return if a state was created? The answers are varied in the <PERSON> Rantisi </PERSON> family as they are among Palestinians as a whole. But there is a shared, strong sense of national identity, enhanced by pride in the success of the intefadeh, the Palestinian uprising in Israeli occupied lands. Sitting on a cardboard box and sipping tea in his grocery store near the Wehdat refugee camp in <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Isa </PERSON> <PERSON> Samaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rantisi </PERSON>, 44, recalled that he had grown up with stories about massacres and expulsions and learned to hate Israelis. `` Now I have become older and have more learning. We can not throw the Israelis in the sea. We want that we live and they live, and to give both peoples a right to coexist,'' said <PERSON> Isa </PERSON> <PERSON> Samaan </PERSON>. In the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Randa </PERSON> <PERSON> Rantisi </PERSON>, 30, is a teacher whose students are active participants in the 15-month Palestinian revolt. She said a mini-state in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> was not enough. `` I want to go back and live where my parents lived before. If <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> wants only the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, maybe others like -LRB- guerrrilla leader -RRB- <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Habash </PERSON> will continue fighting for the rest of <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION>,'' she said. <PERSON> Randa </PERSON>'s older brother <PERSON> Ibrahim </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalil </PERSON> was more concerned about the loss of business during the uprising than about the political future. He is nonetheless indignant at the three times soldiers forced their way into his house looking for stone throwers and at being ordered on another occasion to clear a street of burning tires and barricades. <PERSON> Hoda </PERSON>, 60, mother of <PERSON> Randa </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ibrahim </PERSON>, recalls proudly that her cousin, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Habash </PERSON>, helped carry her daughter during the long trek out of <LOCATION> Lod </LOCATION> in July 1948. `` He looked very sad and was saying over and over, ` God is with us and he will help us.''' <PERSON> Habash </PERSON>, a pediatrician, went on to become leader of the radical Marxist Popular Front for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION>, and is now a leading opponent of <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s renunciation of terrorism and recognition of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Audeh </PERSON>, 52, said the two-day forced march from <LOCATION> Lod </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> was a bitter experience that left deep psychological wounds. The experience helped propel <PERSON> Audeh </PERSON> into politics. He was elected deputy mayor of <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION> in 1976 but deposed by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities in 1982 for refusing to cooperate with the army's newly created civil administration. <PERSON> Audeh </PERSON>, a thin, intense, scholarly looking man who wears a black frock and white collar, said the `` psychological healing process'' will take many years, but that he is ready to turn the other cheek and make peace. `` I do not have hatred in my heart ... I am ready to forgive, but not to forget my rights. God is a God of justice and righteousness,'' said <PERSON> Audeh </PERSON>. <PERSON> Audeh </PERSON> has no desire to move back to <LOCATION> Lod </LOCATION>, saying his life now revolves around his ministry and a private school he runs in <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION>. But he said statehood would bring back his brothers from overseas and reunite the family. Would his family return? <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> <PERSON> Rantisi </PERSON>, who moved to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> 20 years ago `` seeking a better life,'' said he was ready to give up his suburban home near <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, and take his wife and two children to <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION> the instant a state was created. This sense of nationalism is reflected by his 14-year-old daughter <PERSON> Madelane </PERSON>, who seems far more likely than her father to realize such a dream. `` I do n't say I'm a Canadian. I say I'm a Palestinian if anyone asks,'' she told a reporter. But most of the <PERSON> Rantisi </PERSON> family living abroad gave uncertain answers about whether they would risk uprooting their families. `` It's not easy to leave,'' said <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON>, 40, who owns the Uptown Restaurant with his brother <PERSON> John </PERSON>, 30, in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION>. Memories of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> are romantic: sweet plum and almond trees, soft breezes and a slower pace of life. `` It's a happy life without the complications. ... Here there's too much to worry about _ money, bills etc.'' said <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>'s gold market, leaning over a counter filled with earrings and pendants, <PERSON> Isa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ibrahim </PERSON> <PERSON> Rantisi </PERSON> recalled that he visited his birthplace in 1967 and found a Jewish family from <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> in the house. When he went inside the house, `` I remembered everything, it was like a photograph.'' <PERSON> Isa </PERSON> said he did not blame the Israeli family who rented the house, but said he could not give up his right to return and reclaim what belonged to his family. `` How could we give it up?'' he asked. `` If I do n't get it back, my son will.''
