<HEAD>``No Way You Can Forget Your Homeland.'' ^With BC-Palestinains, b0524,b0525</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rantisi </PERSON> have built a life in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, but their hearts and minds often are in a faraway land, where they knew the joy of being united with family and the pain of seeing their world torn apart. Today, the Palestinian brothers are <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens, grateful for freedom and success in their adopted country, but worried about and longing for the simple, yet turbulent, homeland they left behind. `` It's impossible to forget your language, your home and your people,'' said <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON>, 40, who with his younger brother <PERSON> John </PERSON> owns a restaurant in this industrial city. `` I am willing to be a good citizen of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` -LRB- But -RRB- there is no way you can forget your homeland. When you grow up in a place, you learn to love that place.'' `` I remember my friends,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON>, smoking a cigarette as he and his brother sat in a booth in their restaurant. `` It's my home. It's inside of me.'' From a cramped single room they shared in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION>, the 11 children born to <PERSON> Sulieman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Rantisi </PERSON> have migrated to all corners of the world _ <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, Three are in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> with their mother. <PERSON> Sulieman </PERSON> died in 1974. Two brothers, <PERSON> Jaber </PERSON> and <PERSON> Audeh </PERSON>, remain in <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION>. Their cousin, <PERSON> Audeh </PERSON>, an Episcopal priest also lives there. A sister, <PERSON> Nadia </PERSON>, lives in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. The family keeps in contact with letters and phone calls. The <PERSON> Rantisi </PERSON> brothers, who are Christians, grew up with the state of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Shortly after <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers forced most Palestinians out of <LOCATION> Lod </LOCATION> during <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s war of independence in 1948, <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> was born in a cold cement room in <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION> without doctors or nurses. In the following decades, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> conquered the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and the family lived with the turmoil of tanks in the streets, fear of bombings and worries about eviction. But the brothers, who built furniture in a small shop, also have fond memories of sweet plum and almond trees, soft breezes and a slower pace. `` It's a happy life without the complications like here,'' <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> said. `` Over here, there's too much to worry about _ money, bills. ...'' In 1976, <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON>, came to <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. His in-laws lived there and husband and wife began working in factories. `` We thought we could have a better opportunity here,'' <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> said. `` -LRB- There -RRB- the economic situation was very bad.'' There were other motivations. `` You're not free there,'' he added. `` If there's a demonstration or a bomb, it makes everybody fear they're going to be arrested. ... There is no peace.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON>, 30, a bachelor, followed in 1979 and also worked in a factory. They saved their money and though they had no restaurant experience, they bought a small coffee shop in 1985. The brothers work 13-hour days, seven days a week, washing dishes, cleaning and cooking in their Uptown Restaurant, which is simply decorated with salmon-colored <ORGANIZATION> Formica </ORGANIZATION> tables and brown Naugahyde booths. `` We did n't get rich here but we have a better standard of living,'' said <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON>. He said he and his wife speak Arabic at home and try to instill Palestinian culture in their three children. The brothers say they are tied by blood and spirit to the land they still call Palestine and are troubled by the violence of the intefadeh, the uprising against <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> occupation in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. `` When you see it on TV, especially when they beat a person, 10 years old, or 12 years old, or a lady ... you get upset, you get angry,'' <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> said. `` It's a very, very evil thing that they treat human beings like that. ... I know it happens in different countries ... but when you see this happen to your own country, your own people ... I do n't think God himself justified this.'' `` The <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> are suffering in a way like the Jews suffered from the Germans,'' he continued. `` -LRB- By -RRB- beating people and shooting people, breaking their arms, breaking their noses ... it's the same Killing is killing. Suffering is suffering. You ca n't justify what <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> did and you ca n't justify what the Israelis are doing against the Palestinians. The brothers are hopeful a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state will emerge, though they are n't certain how it would affect their lives. A settlement is needed soon, <PERSON> John </PERSON> said, `` before it's too late, before people get more anger and more hatred.'' But <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> said if one comes, `` I do n't see it's going to last for too long. Neither one will be satisfied with their share.'' Would they return? <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> said he might try to open a business, but would have to give it careful consideration. `` I live here 12 years,'' he said, `` it's not easy to leave.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> agreed. `` If I go back home one day,'' he said softly, `` I'm going to miss <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.''
