<HEAD>With BC-Palestinians, b0524, b0525</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This is a metropolis of refugees. The capital of one country, it is filled with Palestinians who cherish dreams of another country across the <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION> was a dusty backwater of 35,000 people when the first Arab-Israeli war broke out in 1948. That conflict, and its successor in 1967, flooded <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> with refugees and many of them settled in and around the capital. Today, about 70 percent of the 1.2 million residents of <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION> are Palestinians, making it the largest urban concentration of Palestinians anywhere. Well-educated Palestinians, many sending home money from jobs in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, helped make <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> into one of the Third World's success stories despite the country's lack of natural resources Expensive cars roam <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>'s streets and spacious houses sprawl across its hills. Shops sell French cheeses, Italian clothes and Danish furniture to a population that averaged more than $ 2,000 per capita a year in income before an economic recession set in two years ago. The Palestinian stamp is evident in the savory aroma of <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> sweets wafting from bakeries, and in the elaborately embroidered <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> dresses worn by many women. Young men wear the black-checked kaffiyeh headdress that has become an emblem of the Palestinian uprising against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 21-year occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> of the <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> But Palestinians in <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION> find themselves torn between two nationalities: that of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and that of a new Palestinian state declared in November by the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. That conflict led to a war in 1970 and the defeat of Palestinian guerrillas by <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>'s Bedouin army. Palestinians refer to the supression of the Palestinian state within <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> as `` Black September.'' But for many, there is no conflict. They hope to remain in <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> at least part of the time even if they gain a state in <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION>. `` I do n't see that there has to be a choice,'' said <PERSON> Hazem </PERSON> <PERSON> Nuseibeh </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Jordanian </LOCATION> foreign minister who comes from one of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s most prominent Palestinian families. `` To the contrary, I think if there is a solution it will be the creation of a Jordanian-Palestinian confederal union.'' <PERSON> Isa </PERSON> <PERSON> Samaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rantisi </PERSON>, 52, an <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION> grocer, expressed gratitude toward the country that sheltered his impoverished family some 40 years ago, when it crowded into a one-room storefront in an <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION> ravine. `` They gave us everything here, more than any other <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> country,'' he told a reporter. `` We do n't think of ourselves as strangers.'' But his 18-year-old nephew <PERSON> Raed </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamali </PERSON>, like many youths in <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>, said he yearns to go home to a country he has never known. `` If I could go, I would go. It's my country, we should go back,'' said <PERSON> Shamali </PERSON>, who wore a scarf fringed in the green, black, white and red colors of the Palestinian flag as he served customers in the crowded store. In 1950, <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> annexed the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and gave the Palestinians citizenship in <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> lost the terrority to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war. King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> in 1988 renounced claims to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, declaring `` <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> is not Palestine'' _ a reference to proposals from Israelis that <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> serve as the Palestinian state rather than let refugees reclaim property in what is now <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> said Palestinians in <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> would have `` all the rights and privileges'' of Jordanian citizens until a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state is created.
