<HEAD>Legislators, Activists Prepare for Abortion Battles</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This is another in an intermittent series anticipating the Supreme
Court's April 26 hearing on abortion regulation. Stephen Freind in 26th
graf cq.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA LEVITT RYCKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 In statehouses across the country, lawmakers fear any significant alteration to <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> could trigger a political war that would make their years as reluctant soldiers in the abortion battles seem like a skirmish. The landmark 1973 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision legalizing abortion ended most of the fierce struggling over the issue in state legislatures. But with the court reconsidering the issue, legislators are worrying about a return to the incessant emotional wrangling that preceded the ruling. `` If they overturn -LRB- Roe -RRB-, it will be the most tragic thing to happen in a long time,'' said Rep. H.L. <PERSON> Jensen </PERSON>, a Democrat from <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, who is the state <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> minority floor leader. `` It will really be a nightmare.'' The high court is scheduled to hear arguments April 26 on <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> abortion regulations struck down last July by the 8th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. Groups on both sides of the issue believe the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> might use the case to modify, if not overturn, the <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> decision. Thirty-four states banned or severely restricted abortions in 1973, and 15 states still have anti-abortion laws on the books, although legal experts say it is not clear they could take effect if <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> was reversed. `` Gosh, I hope they do n't stir that up again. -LRB- It -RRB- was one of the worst things I've been through as a legislator,'' said Republican Rep. <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Littlejohn </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, recalling the pre-Roe days when strident, sign-carrying abortion foes jammed the statehouse to protest <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>' liberal law. The appeals court struck down key provisions of the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> law that banned use of public hospitals or public employees for abortions, prohibited use of taxpayer money for abortion counseling, required doctors to test a fetus older than 19 weeks for viability and declared that life begins at conception. Most states stayed out of the case, but a few decided to enter the fray. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, which boasts of having the nation's most stringent anti-abortion laws on the books, was joined by <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> in filing a brief with the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> supporting <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>'s position. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, which won a 1988 court case blocking <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration efforts to ban abortion at federally financed family planning clinics, filed a brief arguing against Missouri. Its brief was signed by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. Most states have adopted a wait-and-see attitude, but forces on both sides of the issue have begun mobilizing support. `` I'm sure if they overturned the decision, there will be at least a dozen legislators jumping in with bills,'' said <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Maffei </PERSON>, legislative aide to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> state Sen. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardinale </PERSON>, a recently announced <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidate for governor. `` It would be a knock-down, drag-out fight decided by half-dozen votes one way or the other.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s decision in the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> case, expected in July, would come too late for the battles to begin this year; instead, most legislators see themselves starting the new decade under siege if <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> is altered. `` That would tie up every legislature in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in a bitter debate,'' said <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorham </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Rhode </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> minority leader. For some, such as <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, that means the continuation of a no-win struggle that began in 1973 to whittle away at <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> on a local level. Last year, business stopped for several days in the <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> while anti-abortion lawmakers filibustered a budget bill amendment to ease restrictions on Medicaid financing of abortions. Pro-choice legislators hold a one - or two-vote margin in the <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> _ not enough to stop a filibuster but sufficient to block anti-abortion legislation The result is a stalemate, a situation not likely to change. `` There is a gridlock with very, very strong, intense views that seem not to be able to get either position to move,'' <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> said. `` That's the reality of this state.'' A reversal by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> likely would trigger new legal fights over whether the anti-abortion laws still on the books in 15 states could take effect. In <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, for example, the old law required all abortions to be approved by a hospital board and performed in a hospital. The old laws in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> made all abortions illegal except those to save a mother's life. In <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, the pre-Roe law provided for a prison term of up to five years for anyone convicted of performing an abortion. Abortion opponents have kept the issue alive in many states as much as the courts have allowed. Two dozen states have passed laws that mandate parental consent for abortions for minor women, parental notification or both, and 10 or so are considering such bills this year. All but a dozen states have cut off Medicaid financing of abortions for poor women; in many of those states, efforts to restrict that money come up year after year. In <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, for example, the legislature has passed abortion-funding limits every year for the last decade, only to have them struck down by state courts. Fights over such restrictions, while often heated and disruptive, would pale next to the battles that might ensue if the justices were to return abortion to state control, some observers say. `` Once it goes back to the states and people will be playing with real bullets, it's a whole different ballgame,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, a Democrat from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION>. Many legislators predict a reversal of <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> would result in the issue dominating the legislative and electoral processes in many states. `` I've always said that if the court overturns on Tuesday, we'd introduce legislation on Wednesday to outlaw abortions,'' said <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> lawmaker <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Freind </PERSON>, leader of the anti-abortion forces in that state's <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> `` Any meaningful debate on any other public policy would come to a standstill,'' said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Moe </PERSON>, majority leader in the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` The question would be: Are you for or against abortion? That's how candidates would be picked, regardless of how they stand on other important matters.''
