<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Louisiana, 14 Other States Have Anti-Abortion Laws on Books</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Abortion-Legislatures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first battles following any major change in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s 1973 ruling legalizing abortion probably would erupt in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and 14 other states that still have anti-abortion laws on the books. The laws now are unenforceable because of the <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> decision, but there is debate over whether they could take effect if the high court ever overturned the 1973 ruling. The issue would head immediately for the courts. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s law says that if the high court ever reverses the 1973 decision, the state's anti-abortion rules go back into force. <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> have similar laws. `` Our law is broad and general and says the state can regulate abortions totally within limits of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions,'' said <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Lavert </PERSON>, a staff attorney for Attorney General <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Guste </PERSON>. However, Democratic state Rep. <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, who has written most of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s anti-abortion laws since 1973, said he doubted the laws could take effect again and predicted a new law would have to be passed. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Stier </PERSON>, an assistant attorney general in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, which has an anti-abortion law on the books from before the 1973 ruling, said he was not sure what would happen. `` Until we get a decision, it's so speculative it would be a waste of time to guess what the effect would be on <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> law,'' he said. `` There are an infinite number of possibilities of what might happen to the laws on our books.'' <PERSON> Stier </PERSON> said he would advise district attorneys not to begin prosecuting women for violating state law if the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> reversed <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, an assistant state attorney general in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, said his office could not speak specifically about the state's 1852 anti-abortion law unless the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> overturned <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>. But he said there had been previous cases in which old state laws went back into effect after the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> reversed itself. The other states with anti-abortion laws pre-dating <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> are <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, Connectituct, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. An attempt to repeal <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION>'s law has passed the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and is now before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> officials contend the anti-abortion law the state enacted in reaction to <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> is the most stringent in the nation. Before 1973, abortion was a criminal offense in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. Anyone giving an abortion could get up to 10 years in prison at hard labor. Since then, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> has passed many anti-abortion laws that have been found unconstitutional by the courts. Among the provisions thrown out were rules forbidding abortions in the first three months of pregnancy, requiring doctors to test the fetus to see if it could live, mandating parental consent for minors and requiring abortions to be performed only at hospitals by physicians. The only two provisions upheld prohibit public financing for abortions and require that parents of minors be notified of plans for an abortion.
