<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Activists: New York Could Become Abortion Capitol Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Abortion-Legislatures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> was the nation's abortion capital before the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> legalized abortions nationwide in 1973, and it likely would emerge again as a haven if the court ever reversed the <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> decision. Women wanting to end their pregnancies would have more options than they did 16 years ago, when 34 states outlawed abortions, but <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> still has very liberal rules on who may have an abortion. Some states allow the procedure only because of <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> and would see renewed attempts to outlaw or restrict abortions. Fifteen states still have anti-abortion laws on the books, although there is debate whether they could take effect if <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> was reversed. `` <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> would retain the abortion laws it has now and women from other states would come in here to get freely accessible abortions, which would be a burden'' on health services, predicted <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Benshoof </PERSON>, director of reproductive freedom for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. Under <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s law, abortions are permitted up to the 24th week of pregnancy, as long as they are performed by a physician. Abortions after 24 weeks are allowed if a woman's life is in danger. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> is one of just 12 states that still provide Medicaid money for abortions for poor women, and it was the only one of the 16 states permitting abortions before 1973 that did not restrict abortions to state residents. In neighboring <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, by contrast, women under age 18 are required to get their parents' consent for an abortion. The state also requires women to be hospitalized for the procedure and to report it to state authorities. Things are even more restrictive in some parts of the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Benshoof </PERSON> said. She said she knows of women who have flown into <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for abortions from <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, where abortions are prohibited after 20 weeks of pregnancy. `` All these reasons make abortion more delayed and more expensive,'' she said. `` These women would want to come to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to avoid humiliation and unnecessary delay.'' That was the practice during the brief period between the legalization of abortion in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in 1970 and the <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> ruling. Young women stopped flying to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> and instead came to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In 1972, a record 281,000 abortions were performed in the state. By 1974, the first year after <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, the number had fallen to 162,000 and has been relatively constant ever since.
</TEXT>
