<FIRST>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv09   04-04 0957</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 09,0977</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Consumer Food Prices Creep Up Moderately, Says USDA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Barring another big <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drought or a major disruption of international markets by sudden global losses in crop or energy production, it looks like another year of moderate food price increases for American consumers. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is forecasing that retail food prices may rise 3 percent to 5 percent in 1989, about in line with the upward creep of recent years. That estimate averages 12 monthly projections. But food ecomomist <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Parlett </PERSON> says the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> forecast could be revised later this month following a review of the price situation for the first three months of this year. `` What we're looking at, primarily, is that we've gotten so much stronger first-quarter prices, particularly in fruits and vegetables, than we had anticipated,'' <PERSON> Parlett </PERSON> said. `` We sort of missed ... with the cold weather in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, and some in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> too.'' According to the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, if the 1989 forecast is revised upward by a full percentage point _ to a range of 4 percent to 6 percent _ and if it proves to be accurate, the gains in food prices would be the highest in eight years. In 1988, the average of monthly food prices rose an average of 4.1 percent, the same as in 1987. The annual increases previously included: 8.6 percent in 1980, 7.9 percent in 1981, 4 percent in 1982, 2.1 percent in 1983, 3.8 percent in 1984, 2.3 percent in 1985 and 3.2 percent in 1986. <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunham </PERSON>, another <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> analyst, notes in a new review that food costs `` rose at a much higher rate in the second half of 1988 than in the first half due to the severe drought and other market factors.'' By December, he said, prices were 5.2 percent higher than in December 1987, the biggest jump since 1980. The average 4.1 percent increase in last year's food prices was exactly in step with the broader rise in living costs as measured by the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>. In 1987, when food prices also rose 4.1 percent, the overall index gained just 3.6 percent. Economists look at two major components: food sold in grocery stores for use at home, and meals and snacks consumed away from home. The two rose at almost identical average rates over the entire year. But measured from December to December, food prices in grocery stores went up much more rapidly, partly because last summer's drought boosted prices for fresh vegetables, cereals and bakery products, eggs, and fats and oils By December, the food-at-home index was up 5.6 percent from a year earlier. Food served in restaurants, which is affected less by the costs of raw products, increased only 4.4 percent from December to December. <PERSON> Dunham </PERSON> said the cost of the traditional market basket of food items used to compare retail, marketing and farm values from year to year rose 3.5 percent in 1988. The market basket includes only grocery items produced on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farms. It does n't include imported products or seafood. One of the features of the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> market basket analysis is the `` farm value'' of various products. It is a translation of prices received by farmers into an equivalent amount for a specific item or quantity of food. For example, the average retail price of a pound of Choice-grade beef, as measured on an all-cut basis, was $ 2.55 in 1988. The producer's share, or farm value, was $ 1.47, or 58 percent of what shoppers paid. But that does n't mean live cattle sold for $ 1.47 per pound because it takes 2.4 pounds of live animal to make one pound of supermarket beef. Items that require lots of processing _ beef does not, relatively speaking _ show much smaller farm values. A one pound loaf of white bread, for example, sold for 61 cents last year. The farmer's share for all ingredients was five cents, or 8 percent. And that was up a penny from 1987. Overall, the farm value of market basket food in 1988 represented about 30 percent of the total, unchanged from 1987 and the smallest farmer's share of the consumer food dollar since <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> began compiling such figures more than 75 years ago. Department records show the farm value or share of the food dollar averaged 46 percent in 1913. The prevous low mark was 32 percent in the early 1930s; the high was more than 50 percent in World War II and for several years thereafter. Some economists, including <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s Parlett, say that the trend to a smaller share for the farmer also reflects a growing consumer preference for a greater degree of processing in food. Hundreds of preparations, microwave items and many others commonly found in today's supermarkets were unheard of a few years ago. It adds up to huge spending on food. In 1988, according to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> analysts, consumers spent an estimated $ 394 billion in 1988 for foods produced on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farms, up $ 19 billion or about 5 percent from 1987. That includes both meals at home and away from home. Some $ 97.5 billion, or about 25 percent of the total spent, was returned to farmers, a weighted blend of the 30 percent share for food at home and the much smaller 16 percent share of spending for food eaten away from home. In 1987, the farm share was $ 92.8 billion. The remaining $ 297 billion, or the `` marketing bill'' to get food from the farm to consumers, went to the food industry for handling, processing and retailing food after it left the farm. That was up $ 14 billion.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 9</NOTE>
