<HEAD>Oil Futures Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crude oil futures declined in nervous trading after near-normal activities resumed at the <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, port, which was partially blocked after a recent oil spill by an <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> tanker. Wholesale home heating oil also declined Monday, but unleaded gasoline gained almost a penny a gallon on what analysts called seasonal demands. Crude prices started out stronger but fell by midday after news surfaced that the daily pipeline flow at <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> had been increased to 1.3 million barrels. `` Crude had been overbought from the Valdez crisis,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Steele </PERSON>, an energy analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` The opening of the pipeline further relaxed the situation.'' The pipeline usually carries 2 million barrels of crude a day. But that was reduced to 800,000 barrels a day after the spill, causing shortages at <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> refineries and sending oil prices higher. The Alaskan pipeline carries nearly one-quarter of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' domestic supply of crude oil. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the May contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, slipped 24 cents to settle Monday at $ 19.95 a barrel. The contract had lost 62 cents on Friday. Among refined petroleum products, the May contract for heating oil fell 0.62 cent to 52.75 cents a gallon. The April contract had gained 0.71 cent on Friday, the day it expired. May unleaded gasoline settled at 67.85 cents a gallon, up 0.88 cent. The April contract, which also expired Friday, had ended the week with a 2.12 cents gain.
