<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has upped the ante in what could be a high-stakes, match-me incentive game by offering interest-free financing on two-year loans for all of its cars. The nation's No. 3 automaker made the move Monday, five days after <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> challenged the other automakers with 2.9 percent financing for two-year terms. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> followed <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s lead a day later. Interest-free automobile financing was last offered in September 1986 by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> bought less than a year later. Chairman <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Bidwell </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the corporation's car-making arm, called the free financing deal `` the ultimate in APR -LRB- annual percentage rate -RRB- programs. `` It ca n't get any lower,'' he added. `` It ca n't get any simpler.'' In addition to the low financing for two-year terms, each of the Big Three also expanded and boosted some of their cash rebates and offered 5.9 percent financing for three-year loans and 6.9 percent for four-year notes. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> will write a five-year loan for 9.9 percent, 1 percentage point lower than <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s rate for a 60-month term. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s program runs indefinitely. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s expires May 31 and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s runs out June 5. For a customer financing a $ 13,000 car with $ 1,000 down, meaning a $ 12,000 loan, the monthly payments on a two-year loan would be $ 500 under <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s interest-free incentive, and $ 515.24 under <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s 2.9 percent plans. A two-year loan at 11 percent, a common open-market rate, would be $ 559.29 a month. For a more-common 48-month loan, a buyer of either a <ORGANIZATION> Chrylser </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> car would pay $ 286.80 under the 6.9 percent loans offered by the Big Three. With a market-rate loan of 11 percent, a 48-month loan would come to $ 316 monthly. Each of the companies acknowledged that the incentives would cut into their profits, and <PERSON> Bidwell </PERSON> said the company's earnings during the first six months of 1989 would be below last year's levels, and then rebound in the second half. But automobile analyst <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> disagreed. `` I think the gradual increase you've seen in sales incentives over the last three or four months will have a significant impact,'' he said. `` I think <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings are likely to be flat. A few months ago, I was looking for a good-size increase.'' The incentive war comes on the heels of unexpectedly low early 1989 sales and inventories that have been causing some worry, but no panic, among automakers. Each of the Big Three automakers set ambitious production schedules for the first few months of this year, and there are no large-scale moves to curtail them yet. Car and light truck sales through the first 80 days of 1989 have been running 5.4 percent behind the same period last year, the second-best in the industry's history. Sales figures for the first quarter of the year are due out today. The automakers are hoping that the new incentive programs will give sales a boost during April, when they usually are strong as Americans look forward to summer vacations and weekend driving trips. Interest-free financing affects only two-year loans, which in the past have made up about 12 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s business <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON>, president of loan-making company, said he expected that percentage to double with the new program. He also said the 6.9 percent interest rate for 48-month loans, down from 8.9 percent in <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s previous incentive program, will attract buyers who may have been considering five-year notes. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, unlike <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, has not seen a growing number of repossessions and loan defaults in the five-year loan category, which makes up about 60 percent of the company's vehicle-loan business. The interest-free loan deal was well received by dealers the corporation talked with during the weekend, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Pappert </PERSON>, vice president for sales at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>. But the program is bound to face strong criticism from <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Tonkin </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Late last week, after <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> announced their new incentive programs, <LOCATION> Tonkin </LOCATION> called the incentive war a `` circus.'' He urged automakers to get out of the match-me incentive games and `` lower the prices once and for all and guarantee the public those are the prices.'' But <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Lutz </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, said that wo n't work Rebates frequently are used to bolster the credit-worthiness of a potential buyer by increasing their down payment, he said. `` We would greatly prefer to operate the way we used to operate, ...'' <PERSON> Lutz </PERSON> said Monday, `` but the reality is that is n't the world we live in anymore. Whether we'll ever get out of it is anybody's guess.
