<HEAD>C&amp;S Board Rejects NCNB Buyout Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Citizens and <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is relying on a regulatory shield to fight an unwelcome $ 2.4 billion takeover attempt by the <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a merger that, if completed, would create the nation's sixth-largest bank. The board of the parent company of the <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; S Bank voted unanimously Monday to reject the <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> offer, calling it `` inadequate,'' and saying C & amp; S' management can better serve the bank's customers, shareholders and communities than can <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION>. The surprise bid for <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; S followed a push by <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> into <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> last year, in which it bought into the <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. The move by the <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, N.C.-based corporation drove its stock price up 50 percent, enabling <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> to mount other takeover drives with stock, not cash. `` We have managed this bank for service, growth, profitability and long-term service to shareholders _ not for a quick sale,'' C & amp; S Chairman and Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> A. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said in a statement. `` The board of directors and the management have concluded that this offer is clearly inadequate and not in the best interests of C & amp; S shareholders, customers and employees,'' he said. In a statement Monday night, <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> called its offer `` fair and generous'' and said its legal advisers felt there was no regulatory block to such an acquisition. `` We are determined to proceed, and request the C & amp; S board to reconsider our offer and promptly authorize negotiations,'' the release said. <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> lawyer specializing in bank takeovers, said Monday there is `` some chance'' <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> would respect the wishes of the board. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> is acting as special counsel to C & amp; S. He said C & amp; S is the stronger bank and that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has frowned upon a weaker bank taking over a stronger one. He also said the government is worried about banks that grow radically faster than their peers. Along with the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> acquisition, acquiring <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; S would mean <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> would expand its size threefold in a year. Because of the structure of the <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; S board of directors, he said, <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> could not control it until two years after a takeover and noted that the government had rejected mergers with similar problems because of potential disruptions and discord between the board and the majority stockholders. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, a tax specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Alston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Bird, the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> law firm representing <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; S, said the acquisition might be blocked at the state level because by virtue of having more than 20 percent of its deposits in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> can not be considered a member of the Southeastern banking compact. <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> banks can not be sold to banks outside the compact. He said <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> bank examiners might balk at the prospect of <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> moving <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> capital from <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; S to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> to `` finance a speculative investment in a state outside the region.'' <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION>, the Southeast's largest banking company, surprised <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; S and financial observers Thursday with its $ 2.4 billion stock offer. C & amp; S management was cool to the idea from the start. <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> told <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; S it wanted to begin `` active merger discussions'' within five business days. Also Monday, the C & amp; S' board voted to adopt a new article in the corporation's bylaws, under <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s Business Combination Act, preventing any major shareholders from engaging in a business combination for five years, unless certain conditions are met. The move could make a takeover more difficult. A combined <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> and C & amp; S would create a formidable bank with $ 76 billion in assets. <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> officials characterized their buyout offer as friendly and vowed to leave C & amp; S' managers _ and its name _ in place in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. Under <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION>'s plan, <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; S shareholders would get 1.075 shares of <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> common stock for each of their C & amp; S shares. <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> would have to issue about 66 million new shares to provide <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; S stockholders with the $ 2.4 billion.
