 <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> and legal remedies available to the state _ Legislative leaders are looking into possible legislative proposals aimed at protecting state workers and state public investment in the event of a buyout Asked which items on the list might thwart a takeover, <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> said, `` We do n't know, but we're going to explore every possible avenue.'' Industry analysts said it was unclear what, if anything, state officials could do to block a takeover. `` It makes total sense for them to do what they can, but how much of an impact can they have?'' asked <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivard </PERSON> of Minneapolis-based <ORGANIZATION> Dain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bosworth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. If <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> upholds his promise of expanding the airline and keeping its headquarters in <LOCATION> Eagan </LOCATION>, the state would be worse off by blocking a takeover, said <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Marckesano </PERSON>, an airline analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Janney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. `` No management should be entrenched to the exclusion of a sale,'' <PERSON> Marckesano </PERSON> said. The Legislature moved swiftly in June 1987 to block the threatened hostile takeover of Minneapolis-based <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Dart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> by passing anti-takeover legislation. But the law does not affect <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>, which is chartered in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>. The anti-takeover legislation played a role in the defense of <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION>, but the October 1987 stock market crash _ which slashed millions of dollars from the value of <PERSON> Dart </PERSON>'s holdings _ is largely credited with saving the company from takeover. Analysts have warned that a takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> would almost certainly result in the firing of some of the company's 35,000 employees. Northwest has about 17,000 employees in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> said an additional 70,000 Minnesotans whose livelihood depends on the airline operation also would be affected by a takeover. Monday's <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> suggested that <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> could defend itself from takeover bids by issuing a special dividend to shareholders. <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> could easily raise money for a special dividend, analysts told the newspaper, because it owns 73 percent of its aircraft fleet, the second highest percentage of the eight major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines. <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> could sell the planes and lease them back.
