<HEAD>Dallas Investor Says He Plans No Lockheed Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf pvs, The opening ..., with one graf to UPDATE
with stock price. Picks up 11th graf pvs, Lockheed also ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced the creation of a $ 500 million employee stock ownership plan today, one day after an investor group said it held a 5.3 percent stake in the aerospace company. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> said it would issue 10.5 million new shares for its employee stock ownership plan, known as an <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION>, then buy back the same number of shares on the open market. The buyback was intended to offset the dilutive effects of the plan on the company's oustanding stock, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> said Many companies have used ESOPs as defensive moves against hostile takeover attempts. Last month, <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> defeated an unwanted bid from <ORGANIZATION> Shamrock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, with an <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> as part of its defensive strategy. `` We do n't deny it has defensive characteristics, but that was not the primary purpose for the <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Slayman </PERSON> said today. `` The primary purpose is to create employee incentive tied to shareholder growth and value.'' On Monday, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> disclosed that his group, <ORGANIZATION> Valhi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, has a 5.3 percent stake in <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Slayman </PERSON> said today that the <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> `` had been under consideration here for some time.'' <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> said his group's stake in <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> bodes no takeover attempt of the aerospace giant, a company he said is running just fine as it is. The company has taken defensive steps against <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> in the past. When <ORGANIZATION> Valhi </ORGANIZATION> said last December it wanted to increase its holdings to more than $ 15 million, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> said it was implementing a `` poison pill'' shareholder rights plan. The plan would allow current shareholders to buy newly issued stock at a discount if an outsider buys 20 percent or more of the common stock. The effect would be to make it much more expensive for someone to take over the company. In December, <ORGANIZATION> Valhi </ORGANIZATION> owned 0.63 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s 59.5 million outstanding shares. In midday trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> today, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> fell 87.5 cents to $ 48.87 -LCB- a share, after a delayed opening. The stock rose $ 3 a share on Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> also announced steps today to help reduce its costs. The company said it would phase out its information systems group and sell the group's four units. No asking price was given. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> also said it would sell real estate in <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> made available by the ongoing relocation of its aeronautical systems division to sites in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. The company said its was accelerating the relocation to take advantage of what it called more efficient facilities. These steps and the <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> `` will enhance our competitiveness in a rapidly changing environment where premiums are placed on innovation, efficientcy, quality and focused management,'' <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tellup </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Monday he did not intend to try to take over the aerospace giant, which produces the secret F-117A stealth fighter and is home to the famed `` Skunk Works'' _ the advanced development project area at <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION> plant where such innovations as the P-80, the nation's first fighter jet, and the high-flying U-2 and SR-71 spy planes were developed. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> said he might sell some of his stock if it rises another $ 3. He said he had not considered how many shares of <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> he might buy. `` We view <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> as a well-managed company,'' <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> said in a Friday letter to <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> management, a copy of which he released Monday. `` We have no plans, or desire, to disrupt management. We expect to be a constructive, long-term shareholder.'' <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> said he is investing in <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> because he believes its stock was undervalued late last year due to anticipated cuts in the federal defense budget. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> share prices were at $ 39 and averaged into the low $ 40s when he began acquiring them, he said. In February, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> reported profit from continuing operations rose 3.5 percent in 1988, but profit rose 48 percent if proceeds of the sale of its Dialog computerized information services were included. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> said it earned $ 624 million, or $ 10.37 a share, in 1988, up from $ 421 million, or $ 6.41 a share, the previous year. That profit was boosted $ 182 by the sale of Dialog. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> defense projects include the radar-evading stealth fighter, the Trident 11 nuclear missile, the C-5B transport plane and work on military communications, satellites, and the Strategic Defense Initiative, or Star Wars. The company is also a subcontractor for design work on <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s space station project.
