<HEAD>Portland State Helps Develop Soviet MBA Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Portland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> business courses will be used by the <ORGANIZATION> Khabarovsk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economy </ORGANIZATION> in a new master's degree program that Soviet educators say reflects their country's changing economic structure. The economic restructuring, or perestroika, brings greater financial responsibility and the need `` to be a real businessman,'' said <PERSON> Pyotr </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Konevskih </PERSON>, rector of the institute in <LOCATION> Khabarovsk </LOCATION>, about 30 miles north of the Chinese border and 350 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Khabarovsk </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>'s sister city in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. About 5,000 students attend classes at the institute. `` Our hope is that we'll be putting hundreds of students through this program,'' said <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Molander </PERSON>, program coordinator and chairman of the management department in <ORGANIZATION> Portland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. About 50 students specializing in industrial management are expected to start classes this fall to prepare them for the program. The full program, expected to cost the Soviets $ 250,000, will start in April 1990. `` It will be a great challenge, taking a business curriculum designed for a market economy and Western culture and to use that as a framework to educate a current generation in a centrally engineered economy that is becoming more market-oriented,'' <PERSON> Molander </PERSON> said. Soviet educational and business systems differ greatly from those in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, so the <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> State program will be adjusted to the Soviets' economic system, while retaining basic features like accounting, management, communication and marketing, <PERSON> Molander </PERSON> said. Some concepts, however, do n't translate easily, he said. The term `` marketing'' had to be adopted straight from English into the Russian vocabulary because there was no <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> equivalent, <PERSON> Molander </PERSON> said.
