<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> closed higher but below session peaks on Tuesday as a weak early trend on Wall Street curbed some of the optimism generated earlier in the day by the pound's recovery. Sterling's rise underpinned the market throughout the trading session, easing earlier fears that the British government would have to raise interest rates again to defend the currency. The recovery followed the pound's plunge in Far Eastern trading on Monday. But most of the market's gains were later erased by the weak trend on Wall Street. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 3.2 points, or 0.2 percent, higher at 2,082.8, near the day's low of 2,082.4 which came shortly before the market's close. The index had traded as much as 13 points higher during the morning. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> 30-share index closed 1.9 points better at 1,708.4. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> 500-share index rose 1.07 points to close at 1,186.06. Volume was a moderate 508.2 million shares, up from 397.1 million shares a day earlier.
