<FIRST>r f AM-FarmTrade     04-04 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Trade,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Farm Leader Calls For Protective Farm Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should write a 1990 farm bill on the assumption that the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> will block any chance of substantive progress for easing world agricultural trade restrictions, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm leader said Tuesday. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, said the new legislation should continue the current Export Enhancement Program, which subsidizes the export sale of certain <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural commodities, particularly those that must compete with subsidized <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> farm products. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration wants to see the outcome of the current <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round of talks under the General Agreement of Tariffs and Trade before there is a new farm bill. The current law, passed in 1985, will expire next year. Some want the 1985 law extended a year or two so that any <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> settlement can be considered as new legislation is drafted. `` I do n't think we should write a farm bill based on what we hope will happen in the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> talks,'' <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON> told a news conference. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> are hung up mainly on long-term strategy and by what <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiators insist are distortions caused by certain subsidies and restrictive policies. But <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> officials claim there has been progress in overhauling the community's policies and that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should compromise on some of its goals _ which at one time called for the gradual elimination of trade-distorting farm subsidies and rules. Negotiations resume Wednesday in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> under <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> auspices. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> officials say they have agreed on `` progressive substantial reductions'' in agricultural subsidies, a phrase <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON> said he does n't understand at this point. Asked about <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> claims of already making progress in scaling back some of its agricultural programs, <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON> said he could n't see those actions have amounted to much `` In the total context of world trade, it really has n't been anything at all,'' he said. `` And it has n't done anything long-term.'' <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON> said the Europeans `` must make changes if we are to move toward more rational world agricultural trade'' but that the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> `` refuses to entertain that notion.'' Although <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON> said he was not giving up yet on the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Round </LOCATION> of negotiations _ it has about two years still remaining _ he said there is some danger of agricultural issues taking a back seat to other trade matters. One of the reasons agriculture got attention when the current round began in <LOCATION> Punta </LOCATION> del Este, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, on Sept. 20, 1986, was the skyrocketing costs of government farm programs operated by many countries, including the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON> said. Food costs also were rising in some countries. But farm program costs have come down, partly as a result of higher commodity prices fueled by last year's <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> drought _ and lower support prices ordered by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> under the 1985 farm law. `` There's no question that last year's drought and the resulting higher commodity prices around the world took the pressure out of agricultural talks in this round,'' <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON> said. `` But droughts are temporary, they come and go. And so, the long-term problem is still out there.''
</TEXT>
