<FIRST>u f PM-Boeing-Wiring     04-04 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing-Wiring,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>36 More Incidents Of Crossed Wiring, Plumbing Found On Boeing Planes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crossed wiring or plumbing problems in fire warning and extinguishing systems have been found on 94 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> jetliners, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said today. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said none of the problems directly affected the planes' airworthiness, and all were corrected before the aircraft returned to service On Jan. 31, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> issued an airworthiness directive ordering <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> operators of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> jets to inspect for possible wiring or plumbing problems in fire warning and suppression systems in aircraft engines and cargo holds. The directive was prompted by the discovery of 32 such problems in previous checks of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> planes. Only <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> operators were required to make the checks, but many foreign carriers followed suit voluntarily. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said that of the 63 problems found since the directive was issued, 36 were reported since the last update on March 10. Six were found on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aircraft and 57 on foreign planes. Two problems were found on one aircraft, <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said the names of the foreign carriers would not be released because they reported voluntarily and `` because we feel that would hinder the future flow of information.'' However, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> has said it found wiring problems on two of its 767s, <ORGANIZATION> Australian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> reported wrong connections on fire extinguisher bottles on four of its 737s and Japanese television network <ORGANIZATION> NHK </ORGANIZATION> reported last month that problems were found on 19 747s and 767s operated by <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> All </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>. At the time of the March 10 <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> update, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> officials said they had found an engineering solution to prevent wiring problems and were awaiting <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> approval for it. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said today the engineering changes were undergoing final review at <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> before submission to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> for its approval. He said the changes involve the wiring and plumbing connectors, to `` physically differentiate the connectors so it will be much more difficult to connect them improperly.'' The initial cross-connection problems were reported about a year ago. Since then, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> `` has made a lot of progress looking at our assembly procedures in the factory and the functional tests in the factories,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> also is examining its maintenance manuals to see if instructions need to be clarified and whether there is a need to test the extinguisher and warning system functions when maintenance is carried out, he said. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said `` in the vast majority'' of the problems reported, the fire suppression systems still worked. Both the cargo hold and engine fire extinguisher systems have backups. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said today that 19 of the 63 problems were found in the engine fire warning and supression systems. Of those, 10 were found on 737-300s and 737-400s, three on 767s, five on 757s and one on a 747. Forty-four problems were found in cargo compartment fire warning and extinguishing systems, including 30 on 747s, one on a 757 and 13 on 767s. The 32 problems found before the Jan. 31 directive was issued involved 12 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and 20 foreign aircraft. Eight of those involved engine systems, including four on 737-300s and 737-400s, three on 757s and one on a 747. The remaining 24 involved cargo hold systems: seven on 757s and 17 on 767s. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said that of the total 95 problems, 68 concerned wiring, with 24 such problems in engines and 44 in cargo compartments. The remaining 27 were fire extinguisher plumbing problems, with three in engines and 24 in cargo compartments. All the plumbing problems were on 767s.
</TEXT>
