<HEAD>Corning Reports $41.8 Million Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORNING, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Corning Glass Works reported Tuesday that profits were $ 41.8 million for the first quarter of 1989, a turnaround from a $ 46.8 million loss for the same period in 1988. Last year's first-quarter loss was a result of an accounting change in the way the company figured its retirees' medical benefits. The change resulted in a charge of $ 83.9 million against earnings in the first quarter of 1988. Excluding accounting changes and special credits from both years, <PERSON> Corning </PERSON>'s 1989 first-quarter earnings would have risen 12 percent to $ 41.8 million, or 47 cents a share, compared with $ 36.8 million, or 41 cents a share. Sales for the first quarter, which ended March 26, of $ 534 million were up 18 from last year's first-quarter sales of $ 453 million, said <PERSON> Corning </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Albertalli </PERSON>. `` We continue to anticipate another record year,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Corning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Houghton </PERSON>. Sales were up across the board, <PERSON> Albertalli </PERSON> said, and income from jointly owned or partially owned companies rose 26 percent to a record $ 17.7 million in the quarter.
