<HEAD>New Budget Could Squeeze IRS Further, Congressional Auditors Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, already cutting activities, is likely to face another squeeze next year because President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> budget includes no money to enforce a new anti-drug law and the `` taxpayer bill of rights,'' government auditors said Tuesday. `` We question whether the administration has properly reflected what <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> will need to assure adequate funding of its ongoing activities in fiscal year 1990,'' <PERSON> Jennie </PERSON> <PERSON> Stathis </PERSON>, an associate director of the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee. `` This budget is a real friend of the deadbeats,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.D. </LOCATION>, a member of the oversight subcommittee. `` The folks who do n't meet their tax obligations are going to experience a diminished threat'' with fewer <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> auditors and collectors, <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON> said. He noted that while the budget would require a reduction in the number of tax auditors, it anticipates fewer auditors will produce more revenue. There is nothing in the new budget to help the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> deal with the new drug law; the `` bill of rights,'' which is designed to help taxpayers involved in disputes with the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>, or a new tax to finance catastrophic-illness protection for older Americans, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, acting commissioner of internal revenue. When the agency outlined its needs for the coming year, <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> asked that its budget be increased by $ 1.3 billion, in part to reflect increased responsibilities under the new laws. That increase was scaled back by the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, which, instead, approved a raise of $ 289 million, to $ 5.5 billion. `` I feel the 1990 budget does step us forward in tax administration'' despite some shortcomings, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> told the subcommittee. But in the meantime, he added, `` We are dealing with <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> and look forward to working with <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> to resolve those differences.'' Ms. <PERSON> Stathis </PERSON> said that although the budget for the current year is $ 360 million less than <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> needs, `` <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> is functioning so far without any significant disruption to its basic operations. We are uncertain, however, what lies in store for the rest of 1989.'' In scaling back operations, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> vowed not to reduce assistance to taxpayers or slow processing of returns. The agency is reducing travel, training and purchases of computers and supplies. A hiring freeze was imposed for most occupations. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tobias </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, which represents most <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> workers, said <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> enforcement has suffered to the extent that in just six months the government has lost $ 1 billion in revenues that it otherwise would have collected. Another $ 1 billion will be lost by October unless the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> is given more money, he added. This year's squeeze was caused, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said, because of a mandated 4.1 percent increase in employee pay, higher postal rates and a rise in premiums for workers' health insurance and pensions. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, an arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> budget for next year is suspect because it fails to include some costs, including the anti-drug law and the taxpayer bill of rights, while anticipating savings that are questionable. The latter was a reference to <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> projections that the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> can save a considerable amount of money by having private contractors, rather than federal workers, do certain jobs. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>, which has been under intense criticism because its workers incorrectly answer taxpayers' telephoned questions about 30 percent of the time, was criticized by <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> for spending $ 57 million this budget year trying to improve that record. `` Although the initiative is important ... <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>' decision to fund it and other initiatives in 1989 added to the budgetary problems in other parts of the agency,'' Ms. <PERSON> Stathis </PERSON> said.
