<HEAD>Wealthy Art Collector Pleads Guilty to Harassing Her Broker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A socialite art collector who tormented her stockbroker by telephoning him 1,208 times in one week has pleaded guilty to aggravated harassment, been fined and ordered not to contact the man for three years. <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> <PERSON> Scull </PERSON>, 67, claimed she lost thousands of dollars in the October 1987 stock market crash by following tips of broker <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> vice president. But prosecutors said <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> helped Mrs. <PERSON> Scull </PERSON> make $ 300,000 months before the crash by putting her money into government bonds. They said Mrs. <PERSON> Scull </PERSON> made the calls during a week in January 1988, including one day when she telephoned him 485 times. She was arrested on harassment charges Feb. 1 and failed to keep a court date Feb. 28. A warrant was issued for her arrest. After she surrendered and pleaded guilty Monday to aggravated assault charges, <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> Criminal Court Judge <PERSON> Renee </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> fined her $ 1,000 plus $ 60 in court costs and ordered her not to call, write or go near <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> for three years. Mrs. <PERSON> Scull </PERSON>, formerly married to taxi entrepreneur <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Scull </PERSON>, was awarded art works worth millions of dollars in her divorce settlement in 1974. Her collection included pieces by <PERSON> Jasper </PERSON> <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>.
