<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday said it would not stand in the way of <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 1.5 billion investment in <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cellular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's biggest cellular phone company. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said the purchase of a 22.4 percent share of <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> did not involve a transfer of control of <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> and it also was in line with federal restrictions on foreign involvement in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> broadcasting or common carrier companies. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Brock </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s common carrier bureau, said the 1934 Communications Act limits foreign stakes in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> communications companies to either 20 percent or 25 percent, depending on whether the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> concern has direct or indirect control of broadcast licenses. He said <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> does not hold licenses directly, but rather controls them through wholly owned subsidiaries. Thus he said the 25 percent limit applies. <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecom </ORGANIZATION> will gain control of four of the 19 seats on <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION>'s board and acquire 22.4 percent of its stock. The deal is the largest yet for the fledgling cellular industry, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Cellular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORG