<HEAD>Aerospace Company Says Restructuring Unrelated To Investor's Buy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday a reorganization that includes the creation of an employee stock plan was unrelated to investor <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' purchase of 5.3 percent of the aerospace company's stock. The restructuring plan also includes the sale of <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s computer operations and acceleration of a previously announced program to move aircraft manufacturing operations from <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION> and sell about 225 acres of land there That land includes the `` Skunk Works,'' where the F-117 stealth fighter is made. The plan was approved at a board of directors meeting that was scheduled before <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> revealed Monday he had accumulated 5.3 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s 59.5 million shares, said company spokesman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Slayman </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> makes the Trident II missile, the C-5B military transport plane and works on <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s space station project and the `` Star Wars'' missile defense, in addition to other military and aerospace projects. `` There is no denying there are defensive characteristics to these things, but that is not the primary purpose,'' <PERSON> Slayman </PERSON> said of the employee-stock plan, or <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION>, and the other moves. `` The primary purpose is to enhance our competitiveness. This gives -LRB- employees -RRB- a bigger stake in the success of our company.'' <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> _ who also said he planned substantial investments in <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Paccar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ said in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> management last Friday that he did n't intend to try to buy the company. `` We have no plans, or desire, to disrupt management. We expect to be a constructive, long-term shareholder,'' the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> investor said in the letter, which he released to the press Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> would buy 10.5 million newly issued shares of <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> stock for $ 500 million, and the company would offset the dilution of its stock by buying an equal number of shares held by the public. Establishment of the <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> would result in employee ownership of 17 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> common stock, the company said. Such plans are sometimes used to defend against hostile takeovers because it places stock in friendly hands. For instance, an <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> was instrumental in <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s successful defense against a buyout by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Disney </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> adopted a `` poison pill'' takeover defense in December after <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> disclosed he intended to buy up to $ 15 million worth of the company's stock. That plan would entitle current stockholders to buy additional, newly issued stock at a discount in the event of a hostile takeover attempt, thus making a buyout more expensive. On Monday, <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> he intended to invest at least $ 15 million each in shares of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Paccar </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Bellevue </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, truck maker. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s restructuring plan includes: _ The speedup of the previously announced move of <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> from factories next to <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Palmdale </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rye </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canyon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Marietta </PERSON>, Ga The moves, part of a consolidation effort, are to be finished in 1991 instead of 1992 or 1993, as executives previously stated. The move will free 225 acres in <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION> for sale, the company said, revealing for the first time the acreage. _ The four companies or divisions that make up <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s information systems group will be The group, with 3,900 employees, accounted for $ 589 million of the company's $ 10.6 billion in 1988 sales. To be sold are <ORGANIZATION> CalComp </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Anaheim </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> CADAM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Metier </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> and DataPlan of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gatos </LOCATION>.
